  rdfs:label """Interpretation of results and explanation using ideas about surface area to volume ratio and diffusion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564717Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5606-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Plotting and interpretation of a graph showing the effect of sugar concentration on the mass of potato tissue."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564722Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5606-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increase in potato mass means water moved in by osmosis (because the sugar solution was more dilute outside)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564725Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5606-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Decrease in potato mass means water moved out by osmosis (because the sugar solution was more concentrated outside)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564729Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5606-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The concentration of sugar in the potato tissue can be determined from the point at which there was no change in mass."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564733Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5606-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At this point the sugar concentration was equal inside and out, so there was no net movement of water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564737Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5035-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Two unlike electric charges attract each other."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564741Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5035-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Two like electric charges repel each other."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564745Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5035-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In an electric circuit, electrons are forced towards the positive terminal of a battery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564749Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5035-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electric current is the amount of charge that passes a point in a circuit in each second."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564753Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5035-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Current can be found using the equation: current = charge ÷ time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564757Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9889-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Average speed = distance / time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9889-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The speed of sound in air is about 330 m/s."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9889-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Scalar quantities have magnitude only."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9889-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Speed and distance are scalar quantities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564797Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9889-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Relative speed is the speed an object is moving towards or away from another object, which may also be moving."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.564801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5039-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The p.d. across each branch of a parallel circuit is the same as the p.d. across the battery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565263Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5039-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The current through each branch of a parallel circuit adds up to the current through the battery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565267Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5039-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adding a component in a new branch of a parallel circuit reduces the resistance of the circuit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5039-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adding a component to an existing branch of a parallel circuit increases the resistance of the circuit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5039-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The p.d. across the terminals of a battery does not change when components are added to a circuit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4726-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Average speed = distance/time"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4726-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The speed of sound in air is about 330 m/s."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565290Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4726-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Scalar quantities have magnitude only."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565294Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4726-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Speed and distance are scalar quantities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4726-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Relative speed is the speed an object is moving towards or away from another object, which may also be moving."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565303Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5059-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An LDR is made of a semiconductor, and the brighter the light shining on it, the lower its resistance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565307Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5059-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Light transfers energy that enables electrons in a semiconductor to move as they do in a metal conductor."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565313Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5059-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A thermistor is made of a semiconductor, and the hotter it is, the lower its resistance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5059-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Heating transfers energy that enables electrons in a semiconductor to move as they do in a metal conductor."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5059-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A potential divider circuit can be set up with an LDR/thermistor to trigger a switch if it becomes too dark or too cold."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9903-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A velocity-time graph shows how velocity changes with time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565407Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9903-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Acceleration is equal to the gradient of a velocity-time graph."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9903-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A falling line shows decreasing velocity called deceleration, which is a negative acceleration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In all chemical reactions, bonds in the reactants need to be broken before the reaction can happen"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Energy must be supplied to break bonds in the reactants"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565918Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Energy is released when bonds in the products are formed"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565922Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The difference between the energy needed to break bonds and the energy released is the overall energy change"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon atoms will form up to four covalent bonds (as they will fill their outer shell with four more electrons)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565930Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon atoms can combine with other non-metal atoms to make a wide range of molecules, some with chains and rings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An organic compound contains two or more elements (including carbon)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A lot of organic compounds also include hydrogen, oxygen and nitrogen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565942Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Organic compounds can be found both in nature, but also produced synthetically."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565946Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6605-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An appropriate range of p.d. values includes 0 V and the maximum p.d. of the lamp and at least four other readings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565950Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6605-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For electricity investigations, it is good practice to take many more than the minimum number of measurements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6605-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After plotting a graph, extra readings could be taken to fill gaps or to check possible errors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565961Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6605-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Plots that lie off the best fit line are possible errors that need to be checked."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565965Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6605-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The resistance of a filament lamp is calculated from an I–V graph using pairs of readings and the equation R = V ÷ I."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565969Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5044-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Displacement at a point of a wave is the distance that the wave medium is from its rest position at that point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5044-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Amplitude is the maximum displacement of a wave (up or down, or side to side)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5044-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A displacement-distance graph of a wave is not a picture of the wave."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565981Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5044-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The distance between two wave crests on a displacement-distance graph is equal to one wavelength."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565985Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5044-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A positive (or negative) displacement shows part of the wave above (or below) the equilibrium position."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565989Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8153-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Density is calculated using the equation: density = mass ÷ volume."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565995Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8153-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Density is measured in kg/m³ or g/cm³."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.565999Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8153-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volume of water displaced by a submerged object is equal to the volume of the object."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566003Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8153-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The dimensions of a regular cuboid can be measured accurately with Vernier callipers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566007Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8153-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volume of a regular cuboid is calculated using the equation: volume = length × width × height."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566012Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5074-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The magnetic field lines around a current-carrying wire are concentric circles"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566016Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5074-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In a uniform magnetic field, a current carrying wire is forced in one direction"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566022Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5074-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fleming’s left–hand rule can be used to predict the direction of movement of a current–carrying wire in a magnetic field"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566026Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5074-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The force on a current–carrying conductor at right angles to a magnetic field, F, is found using F = B I l."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566030Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5074-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Opposite sides of a conducting coil in a uniform magnetic field are forced to move in opposite directions"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5556-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Safe use of materials and apparatus."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5556-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Accurate measurement of reactants and reagents."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5556-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Control of temperature using a water bath or electric heater."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5556-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Continuous sampling of reaction mixture and testing with iodine for the presence of starch."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566330Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5556-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Sampling at accurately timed intervals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566334Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Polymers are very large covalent molecules (not giant structures)"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566358Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Polymers can be represented by showing repeated units"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566364Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Polymers consist of repeating and identical sections called monomers"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Polymers are solid at room temperature because the intermolecular forces between polymer molecules are relatively strong"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566373Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Catalysts, pressure, temperature & concentration of solutions can affect equilibrium position of a reversible reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566379Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the conditions of a reversible reaction are changed, the equilibrium will move to counteract that change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566383Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A catalyst increases the rate at which equilibrium is achieved."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566388Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing temperature increases the rate of both reactions; equilibrium shifts in favour of the endothermic reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566391Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing the concentration or pressure of a substance increases the rate of reaction; equilibrium shifts in response."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566395Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The periodic table is ordered by increasing atomic number (proton number)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566399Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The periodic table is split into periods and groups."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566404Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The position of an element in the periodic table is linked to its atomic number and the arrangement of its electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566408Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Elements can be classed as metals or non-metals according to their position on the periodic table."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566412Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A useful model for atoms arranges electrons in shells around the nucleus."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5047-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An oscilloscope is a displacement-time graph of a wave"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5047-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Connected to a microphone, an oscilloscope shows a displacement-time graph of a sound wave"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566424Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5047-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The distance between two wave crests on an oscilloscope’s graph is equal to the period of the wave"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566430Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5047-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The time period is measured most accurately by measuring the time for, say, 10 waves and dividing time by 10"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5047-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The bigger the amplitude of a sound wave, the louder the sound"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.566438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9108-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A velocity-time graph shows how velocity changes with time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567264Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9108-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Acceleration is equal to the gradient of a velocity-time graph."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567270Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9108-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A falling line shows decreasing velocity called deceleration, which is a negative acceleration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567274Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4731-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A dynamics trolley has a steady acceleration down a steep ramp."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4731-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Acceleration = change of velocity ÷ time and change in velocity = final velocity – initial velocity"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4731-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Light gates can improve accuracy of measurement of instantaneous velocity and reduces random errors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4731-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "For a fair test, total mass of the system must be kept constant."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567290Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4731-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A compensated ramp can counteract the effect of friction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567294Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6606-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The properties of a diode are different, depending on the direction of p.d. across it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6606-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An appropriate range of p.d. includes 0 V and the maximum voltage of the diode and at least four other readings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567304Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6606-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An appropriate range for a diode includes the maximum p.d. in both directions, with positive and negative values."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6606-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For electricity investigations, it is good practice to take many more than the minimum number of measurements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567312Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9153-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Electric charge, Q, is measured in coulombs (C)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9153-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electric current is a measure of the rate of flow of electric charge, calculated using: I = Q ÷ t."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567405Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9153-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Potential difference is a measure of the energy transferred by each coulomb of charge, calculated using: V = E ÷ Q."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567409Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9153-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Combining I = Q ÷ t and V = E ÷ Q gives the equation: E ÷ t = I × V. This is equivalent to P = I × V."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567414Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9153-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unknown variables in the power equation can often be calculated using: I = V ÷ R."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567419Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9112-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Current can be calculated using the equation: current = p.d. ÷ resistance (I = V ÷ R)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9112-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The rules of current and p.d. for a parallel circuit can be applied to find some missing values of current and p.d."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567427Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9112-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The equation I = V ÷ R can be rearranged so that either p.d. or R is the subject of the equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9112-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If any two values in the equation I = V ÷ R are known, the third can be calculated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567435Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9112-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If only one value in I = V ÷ R is shown for a component, circuit rules need to be applied to the rest of the circuit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567439Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4908-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Doubling the stiffness of a spring doubles the energy it has because it is stretched."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567550Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4908-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The spring constant is measured in newtons per metre (N/m)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567556Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4908-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Doubling the extension of a spring increases the energy it has because, it is stretched, by four times."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567561Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4908-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The energy a spring has because it is stretched equals 1/2 × spring constant × (extension)²."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567565Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5097-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Power is the amount of energy transferred per second and is measured in watts (W)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567569Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5097-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Power can be calculated using the equation: power = current × potential difference (P = I V)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567573Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5097-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At a constant p.d., a larger electric current transfers energy more quickly than a smaller current."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5097-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Domestic appliances plugged into the mains supply in the UK have a p.d. of 230 V across them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567583Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5097-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The fuse with the smallest rating for the required current (calculated using the equation: P = I² R) should be used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567587Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5084-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Refraction is when waves travel from one transparent medium to another, causing a change in direction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567591Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5084-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When waves slow down, they turn towards the normal line (angle of incidence > angle of refraction)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567595Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5084-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When waves speed up, they turn away from the normal line (angle of incidence < angle of refraction)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567599Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5084-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Refraction can be investigated using a clear rectangular block, ray box and narrow slit, pencil, paper and a protractor."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567603Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5084-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Refraction occurs when one side of a wavefront enters the new medium before the other, causing a change in wave speed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.567607Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5050-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The speed of wave can be caluated using wave speed = frequency × wavelength."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568009Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5050-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The speed of a wave can be caluated using wave speed = distance ÷ time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5050-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The choice of equation to use to caluate wave speed depends on the information provided in the question."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5050-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Prefixes can be used with units to show very large or very small values."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568024Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5050-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The frequency of a wave does not change as it crosses a boundary from one wave medium into another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568028Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5046-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a longitudinal wave, the oscillations / vibrations are in the same direction in which the wave travels."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568481Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5046-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Displacement is the distance one part of a wave is moved away from its rest position."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568485Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5046-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a longitudinal wave, forwards displacement is positive and backwards displacement is negative."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5046-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wavelength of a longitudinal wave is the distance between one compression (or rarefaction) and the next."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568493Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5557-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Interpretation of graphs showing data from an investigation of the effect of pH on the rate of an enzyme reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568670Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5557-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Consideration of whether the data increase or decrease confidence in the original prediction or hypothesis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568674Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5557-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Enzyme reaction rate is highest at an optimum pH, at which all active sites are full."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568678Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5557-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Enzyme reaction rate decreases at pH values below and above the optimum as the active site becomes denatured."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568682Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4917-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Stopping distance is the distance travelled, both as a driver reacts and as the brakes to bring a vehicle to a stop."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568686Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4917-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The reaction time of a driver can be affected by tiredness, drugs, alcohol or distractions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568692Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4917-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The braking distance can be affected by adverse road and weather conditions and the condition of the vehicle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568697Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4917-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "When braking, work is done on the brakes that heats them up."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568701Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4917-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If brakes overheat they can stop working effectively and lead to a loss of control."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.568705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9127-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A wire heats up when a current flows and its temperature will vary over time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569251Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9127-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A water bath helps to keep the temperature of a wire constant."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569255Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9127-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Turning a circuit on for a very short time reduces the heating effect in a wire."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569259Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9127-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In electricity investigations, it is often easy to take lots of readings rather than a few, repeated readings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569263Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9127-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The resistance of a wire is directly proportional to its length, at a constant temperature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569267Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5601-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Living yeast cells immobilised in alginate beads will carry out cellular respiration and produce carbon dioxide gas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569351Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5601-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The gas can be collected and the volume of gas measured using an upturned measuring cylinder under water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569355Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5601-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Identifying independent and dependent variables, and variables to control to increase the validity of the results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569359Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5601-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """How to read the volume of gas from the meniscus in the measuring cylinder after a set time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569367Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5601-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Collecting repeat measurements for each substrate, and collecting data for different substrates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569372Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9123-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a fair test, only the independent variable is changed so that no other changes could affect the results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569398Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9123-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The variables that are deliberately kept the same are called control variables."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569403Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9123-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A lid on a beaker prevents transfer of energy by convection currents."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569407Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9123-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Gas is a very poor thermal conductor."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7981-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most characteristics are influenced by multiple genes, but some are determined by just one."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7981-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An individual will inherit two alleles for each gene, the alleles for a gene may be dominant or recessive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569419Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7981-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A Punnett square models inheritance of alleles showing possible genotypes of offspring as homozygous or  heterozygous."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7981-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Punnett squares are used to predict proportion of genotypes/phenotypes, or probability of occurrence in the offspring."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569427Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7981-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Each instance of sexual reproduction is independent, so does not affect the probability for subsequent offspring."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9095-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The particles in liquids and gases move very quickly and randomly in every direction; they are both fluids."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9095-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Particles in liquids are very close together; the gaps between particles in gases are much larger than the particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9095-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The pressure at any point in a fluid is the same size in every direction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569447Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9095-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The particles in a fluid exert pressure on a surface by colliding with it."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9095-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Pressure is calculated using the equation: pressure = force ÷ surface area."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569455Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20342-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A dynamics trolley has a steady acceleration down a steep ramp."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569459Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20342-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Acceleration = change of velocity ÷ time and change in velocity = final velocity – initial velocity"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569464Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20342-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Light gates can improve accuracy of measurement of instantaneous velocity and reduces random errors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569468Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20342-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "For a fair test, total mass of the system must be kept constant."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569472Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20342-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A compensated ramp can counteract the effect of friction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569476Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5552-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All carbohydrates, proteins and lipids are made of the elements carbon, hydrogen and oxygen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5552-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "All proteins and some lipids also contain the element nitrogen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569483Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5552-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Producers obtain carbon and oxygen from the air, hydrogen from water, and nitrogen from the soil."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569487Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5552-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Consumers cannot use carbon from carbon dioxide in air to make biological molecules; only producers can do that."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569491Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5552-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Consumers absorb oxygen from the air but get all their carbon and nitrogen by eating producers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569495Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27996-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Following an appropriate method to vary light intensity and measure the colour change of indicator."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27996-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Accurate measurement of variables (distance, time, colour change); control of variables that might affect the results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569504Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27996-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Comparison of indicator colour to a chart to determine pH."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569508Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27996-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Record results in an appropriate table."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569514Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28973-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Forests act as a global carbon sink, absorbing one-quarter of the annual global CO₂ emissions from the atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569518Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28973-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Deforestation contributes to climate change and is a major cause of habitat and biodiversity loss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569525Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28973-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mitigation strategies include forest protection, reducing deforestation for farming, and replanting trees."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569529Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28973-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Oceans act as a global carbon sink, absorbing one-quarter of annual global CO₂ emissions from the atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569533Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28973-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """High CO₂ levels harm marine biodiversity through ocean acidification and reduced shell formation, alongside overfishing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569537Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5586-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Water and mineral ions are transported from the roots, up the stem, to the leaves, in vessels made of xylem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569541Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5586-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Xylem is made of dead, empty cells with no cytoplasm, that form a tube with a tough wall made of lignin."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569545Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5586-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Water is continually lost from the surface of a plant when water molecules diffuse into the air through open stomata."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569549Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5586-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Water is pulled up through xylem tubes to replace the water lost through open stomata; this process is transpiration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569553Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5586-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The water that is pulled through xylem tubes has mineral ions dissolved in it, including nitrate ions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569557Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27970-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Word and balanced symbol equations for anaerobic cellular respiration in humans, and conditions in which it occurs"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569561Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27970-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Word and symbol equations for anaerobic respiration in plants and micro-organisms, and conditions in which it occurs"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569565Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27970-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Anaerobic cellular respiration takes place only in the cell cytoplasm and does not involve mitochondria"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569571Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27970-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Anaerobic cellular respiration provides less ATP (so less energy) than aerobic cellular respiration, but more quickly"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569575Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27970-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Uses of anaerobic cellular respiration (fermentation) in yeast"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5098-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Electric charge, Q, is measured in coulombs (C)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569606Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5098-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electric current is a measure of the rate of flow of electric charge, calculated using: I = Q ÷ t."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569612Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5098-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Potential difference is a measure of the energy transferred by each coulomb of charge, calculated using: V = E ÷ Q."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569616Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5098-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Combining I = Q ÷ t and V = E ÷ Q gives the equation: E ÷ t = I × V. This is equivalent to P = I × V."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569620Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5098-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unknown variables in the power equation can often be calculated using: I = V ÷ R."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569624Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6387-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Benefits of high biodiversity, including ecosystem services and food security."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569646Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6387-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Humans can interact positively with ecosystems to prevent and reduce biodiversity loss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6387-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Resources can be used sustainably (e.g. at a rate at which they can be replaced)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6387-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A range of conservation measures can be taken to protect biodiversity at the species, ecosystem and genetic levels."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569659Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6387-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Conservation efforts range from very local actions to international ones."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569663Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ozone layer protects life from harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the Sun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569747Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) were once used, and when they entered our atmosphere reacted with ozone (O₃)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ozone levels decreased, but scientific communication led to action being taken to prevent further loss of ozone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569757Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The work of analytical scientists suggests the ozone layer is now reforming."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8315-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atomic number of an element states the number of protons in the nucleus of every atom of that element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8315-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of electrons in an atom is equal to the number of protons in the nucleus of the atom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569770Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8315-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass number of an element is about equal to the number of protons and neutrons in atoms of that element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27585-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Growing food helps feed the increasing human population, but can have negative impacts on ecosystems and biodiversity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27585-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The use of peat and destruction of peat bogs as an example of a negative impact."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27585-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Eutrophication as an example of a negative impact."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569802Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27585-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The introduction of non-indigenous species as an example of a negative impact."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27585-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ways of mitigating some of these negative impacts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.569810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7167-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Vaccines have had a positive effect on public health (e.g. the eradication of smallpox)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570230Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7167-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Vaccination is not risk free as it can have side effects, but the benefits outweigh the risks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570235Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7167-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """New vaccines are trialled, and are only approved for use when the benefits of the vaccination outweigh the risks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570239Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7167-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is necessary to vaccinate a high proportion of a population against a pathogen to provide herd immunity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570243Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7167-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Herd immunity helps protect those who can’t or won’t have the vaccination."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570247Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9902-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A dynamics trolley has a steady acceleration down a steep ramp."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570592Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9902-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Acceleration = change of velocity ÷ time and change in velocity = final velocity – initial velocity"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9902-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Light gates can improve accuracy of measurement of instantaneous velocity and reduces random errors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570600Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9902-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "For a fair test, total mass of the system must be kept constant."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9902-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A compensated ramp can counteract the effect of friction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570608Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5598-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cellular respiration happens continuously in all living organisms to transfer the energy needed for life processes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5598-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cellular respiration is an exothermic chemical process that uses glucose as a fuel."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5598-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Word equation and balanced symbol equation summarises the reactants and products of aerobic cellular respiration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.570996Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5598-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerobic cellular respiration takes place in the mitochondria of eukaryotic cells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571000Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-5598-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerobic cellular respiration takes place in the cytoplasm of prokaryotic cells, which do not have mitochondria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571004Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26663-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All cells, including our body cells and pathogens, have molecules called antigens on their surface."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571040Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26663-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "White blood cells only respond to non-self antigens on pathogens."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26663-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Lymphocytes are an important part of the human immune system and respond to antigens on specific pathogens."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571048Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26663-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Lymphocytes produce antibodies against specific pathogens."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571052Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26663-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Lymphocytes produce antitoxins to neutralise toxins produced by bacteria."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571056Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9194-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The parts of a light microscope and their functions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571181Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9194-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sequence of steps for setting up a microscope to observe specimens, including changing the magnification and focus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571185Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9194-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The steps of applying nail varnish and clear sticky tape to a leaf surface, then observing imprints of stomata."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9194-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Light microscopy can be used to observe and compare the density and distribution of stomata on different leaf surfaces."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571198Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9194-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Explaining observations of stomatal density using ideas about transpiration and water loss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7165-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The human body has defences against infection that work against all pathogens (are not targeted at specific pathogens)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7165-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Physical defences include the skin, hairs and cilia."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571210Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7165-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Chemical defences include tears, saliva and stomach acid."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7165-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Microbial defences are provided by microorganisms on, and in, our bodies that compete against pathogens."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571218Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7165-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """White blood cells called phagocytes are part of the immune system and engulf and destroy pathogens by phagocytosis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571222Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27969-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cellular respiration happens continuously in all living organisms to transfer the energy needed for life processes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571726Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27969-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cellular respiration is an exothermic chemical process that uses glucose as a fuel, and makes ATP."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571730Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27969-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Word equation and balanced symbol equation summarises the reactants and products of aerobic cellular respiration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571734Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27969-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerobic cellular respiration takes place in the mitochondria of eukaryotic cells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571738Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27969-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerobic cellular respiration takes place in the cytoplasm of prokaryotic cells, which do not have mitochondria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571742Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6612-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A soft iron core increases the strength of an electromagnet because it becomes magnetised when it is turned on."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6612-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The more tightly wound the coil of wire is in an electromagnet, the stronger its magnetic field."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571883Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6612-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The greater the current through the coil of an electromagnet, the stronger its magnetic field."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-6612-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The strength of an electromagnet is directly proportional to the current through it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:13.571894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

