# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-clearly-meant-stopping
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often do not understand clearly what is meant by stopping time and cannot explain why longer stopping times result in smaller forces."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Describe stopping time as the time it takes to stop ‘during which a force is acting’, and provide examples of smaller forces stopping moving objects over longer periods of time than larger forces."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.347375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-realise-significance-shape-root
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some students do not realise the significance of the shape of the root hair cell and do not explain this in terms of increasing its surface area."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The idea of surface area as the significant adaptation of root hair cells is clearly introduced, checked, and reinforced with specific tasks that explicitly enquire about this adaptation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.347430Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-ionic-charges-determine-empirical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Using ionic charges to determine the empirical formulae, especially with polyatomic ions. Standard notation is difficult and confusing, e.g. when to use superscripts, subscripts or brackets."""@en ;
  curric:correction """At this stage, pupils will need to just learn the the formulae of the polyatomic ions and accept that a full explanation will come later in their chemistry learning. Provide pupils with plenty of practice of writing and using ionic formulae."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.347475Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-elemental-diatomic-molecule
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that an elemental diatomic molecule, e.g. hydrogen, is a compound because they see two atoms chemically joined together."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The teacher needs to emphasise the definition for compounds. Molecules are not the same as compounds, some molecules are compounds, not all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.347484Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-mistake-common-everyday-usage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils mistake common (everyday) usage of pure (e.g. pure orange juice) as being a pure substance when it is, in fact, a mixture."""@en ;
  curric:correction """'Everyday' usage refers to one source, whereas scientific usage refers to particle composition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.347489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-consider-control-variables-carefully
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some pupils do not consider how to control variables carefully enough. This means results are likely to be less accurate and so do not provide conclusions that can be used to support a hypothesis."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Each type of variable is considered during the lesson and repeated to help pupils to understand the differences between each type of variable."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.347667Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-difference-repeatability-reproducibility
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often struggle with the difference between repeatability and reproducibility."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson outlines the difference between these two aspects of working scientifically and checks pupils understanding of these in relation to the investigation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.347751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-appreciating-increasing-temperature-optimum-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Not appreciating that increasing temperature up to the optimum has a different effect on rate than increasing temperature above the optimum."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The effects on rate of increasing temperature up to and beyond the optimum are explained."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.348346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-use-atomic-number-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may use the atomic number rather than mass when calculating the relative formula mass. Also, the number of atoms can be missed for the percentage of an element in a compound."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that atomic mass is the larger number for each element on the periodic table and encourage pupils to use the key present to help them identify the mass."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.348638Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dominant-allele-stronger-recessive-allele
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The dominant allele is stronger than the recessive allele preventing its expression or that the recessive allele is an absence of the dominant allele, also that all genetic disorders are recessive."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Linking the allele to change in protein structure, showing that proteins are produced in the case of dominant and recessive alleles. Examples of dominant and recessive disorders provided."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-eukaryotic-cells-multicellular
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All eukaryotic cells are multicellular."@en ;
  curric:correction """Addressed within the slides to specifically mention that some eukaryotic organisms are unicellular."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351591Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-features-encoded-genome-visible-phenotype
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That all features encoded in the genome are visible in the phenotype."@en ;
  curric:correction """Give examples of structural and functional proteins that are not visible in an organism's phenotype."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-bacterial-cells-looks-like-bacterial
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All bacterial cells looks like the bacterial cell model."@en ;
  curric:correction """Bacteria can come in different shapes and sizes, this will be outlined within the slide deck."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351603Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-person-either-healthy-unhealthy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A person is either healthy or unhealthy."@en ;
  curric:correction "Health is a range from good to ill health."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-viruses-alive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Viruses are alive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Viruses do not carry out many of the life processes required for living organisms such as respiration and reproduction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351688Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-human-other-animals-catch-diseases
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Only human and other animals can catch diseases. Plant diseases are not important."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson explores examples of plant diseases, the pathogens that cause them and how they are spread, and their devastating impacts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351693Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-linking-idea-glucose-concentration-important
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Not linking the idea that glucose concentration is important for cellular respiration, even during times of rest."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are a selection of slides in LC2 that specifically link glucose and respiration and discuss the idea of respiration occurring during rest."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351697Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-describing-identifying-independent-dependent-control
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Describing and identifying independent, dependent and control variables and following a method with care and accuracy are skills that take time to build and need frequent revisiting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The variables in the practical and the method are outlined and discussed. Considerations on the ethicality of the experiment due to human subjects, and the presence of anomalous data, are also covered in detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351702Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-animals-plant-multicellular
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that all animals and plant are multicellular and that all unicellular organisms are bacteria."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Lesson explicitly addresses this misconception and the questions in Task A are designed to expose the misconception."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351706Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-names-blood-vessels-their-functions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The names of the blood vessels and their functions and adaptations are often confused. Students often forget or misunderstand red blood cell adaptations too."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Both these areas are covered in detail, with clear step-by-step information given and tasks to check learning and reinforce understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-villi-alveoli-increase
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that villi and alveoli increase surface area without changing volume."""@en ;
  curric:correction """These ideas are explored in detail with examples and demonstrations using cube animals. The issue of surface area to volume ratio and diffusion rate is covered thoroughly, along with solutions to the issues in humans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-chromosomes-halved-cell-splits
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Chromosomes are halved when the cell splits."@en ;
  curric:correction "Slides repeatedly address the concept that chromosomes are copied."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351724Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-multiple-misunderstandings-nervous-system-including
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There are multiple misunderstandings about the nervous system, including the order and function of neurones, the roles of the stimulus, receptor and effector, and the central and peripheral parts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The pathway through the nervous system is built up with examples and demonstrated as a flowchart. The roles of the different parts is explained and practised, and distinctions are made between the central and peripheral parts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351731Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-climate-change-affects-weather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Thinking that climate change affects the weather, but not human health."@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson explores direct and indirect impacts of climate change on human health."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351737Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-consumers-including-humans
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is a common misconception that consumers (including humans) could survive without producers."""@en ;
  curric:correction "The dependence of consumers on photosynthesis in producers in explored in depth."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-names-functions-different-parts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Confusion between the names and functions of the different parts of the heart and the direction that blood moves through the heart."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The parts of the heart and their structure and function are dealt with separately and clearly, and followed up with quick checks plus longer and more detailed tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enzymes-used-reactions-enzyme-catalyse
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That enzymes are used up in reactions, or that an enzyme can catalyse many different reactions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Enzymes are not used up in the reactions that they catalyse, and that they can only catalyse one reaction, as explained by the lock and key hypothesis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351824Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cells-inert-building-blocks-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Cells are inert 'building blocks' like bricks. Microscopes can see structures as small as molecules."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores what cells are, including that they are living units, and considers what can and can't be seen using a light microscope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351829Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-commonly-convert-units-incorrectly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils commonly convert units incorrectly, multiplying when they should divide or dividing when they should multiply."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It can help to relate the unit conversions in the lesson to an everyday example, e.g. pounds to pence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351841Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-negative-feedback-works-reverse-high
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Negative feedback only works to reverse high levels back to normal."@en ;
  curric:correction """The slide deck has several slides where changes are described as being high and low and there is a CFU question in the final learning cycle that specifically assesses this misconception."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351846Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-health-claim-product
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that any health claim by a product must be true."@en ;
  curric:correction """Often no scientific research has been carried out on products claiming to be healthy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351851Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-arises-monomers-used-build
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Confusion often arises over which monomers are used to build which polymers."@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson clearly explores carbohydrates, proteins and lipids as separate sections and covers the monomers and the polymers they form with care and repetition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nutrients-waste-either-produced-cell
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Nutrients and waste are either not produced, or not by every cell, with misconceptions about where these substances come from or go to and what the roles of the various systems are as a result."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Key nutrients and waste products are dealt with individually and related to the relevant body systems. These ideas are focused on in main and check tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mixing-prediction-observation-explanation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mixing up a prediction, an observation and an explanation."@en ;
  curric:correction """This practical lesson explores predictions, observations and explanations in the context of using iodine solution to test leaves for starch."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351885Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-constitutes-reflex-response-generated-body
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """What constitutes a reflex response, and how they are generated in the body is often confused and muddled, leading to an incorrect mix between a standard neural pathway and the reflex pathway."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The reflex pathway is clearly stated and explained, and it is compared to the standard neural pathway. Plenty of examples of reflexes are given, including those that occur in other organisms, and there is a quick practical to try too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351904Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-males-y-chromosomes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Males only have Y chromosomes."@en ;
  curric:correction "Males have one Y and one X chromosome."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-people-either-healthy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that people are either healthy or unhealthy."@en ;
  curric:correction "Health is a range from good to ill. Fitness is one indicator of general health."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-photosynthesis-one-simple
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception is that photosynthesis is just one simple reaction, as depicted by the word equation and balanced symbol equation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This explores the idea that the word equation and balanced symbol equation are useful but very simple models of photosynthesis, and also explores a slightly more detailed two-stage model of the process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-viruses-alive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that viruses are alive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Viruses do not carry out many of the life processes required for living organisms such as respiration and reproduction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351949Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nothing-person-decreases-their-risk
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is nothing a person can do to decreases their risk of getting cancer."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although we can't change inherited genetic risk factors for cancer, it does also have many associated lifestyle risk factors such as obesity and smoking."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-malaria-caused-mosquitos
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Malaria is caused by mosquitos."@en ;
  curric:correction "Mosquitos are the vector that transfer the protist to humans."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351968Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-type-1-diabetes-caused-lifestyle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Type 1 diabetes is caused by lifestyle, particularly poor diet."@en ;
  curric:correction """The slide deck states that type 1 diabetes is caused by genes or environmental factors and there is a question in task A to assess this. In contrast there is a big focus on lifestyle and obesity being linked to developing type 2 diabetes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-usually-lot-confusion-synapse-signal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is usually a lot of confusion over the synapse and how the signal moves from electrical, to chemical, to electrical again. There are many new key words involved, which makes it even harder."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The synapse has been broken down into several stages with clear diagrams and carefully used key words. There are plenty of opportunities to practise using the terminology and explaining the process, including applying it to a real-world scenario."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351978Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-misconceptions-mixing-aim-prediction-leaving
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Misconceptions mixing aim and prediction or leaving them vague, writing a method which is unclear, and analysing hazards and their risks."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Approaches for stating aims and predictions, writing a method and dealing with variables, and analysing hazards and their risk are all covered with examples and practice tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mistakes-method-results-confusion-poor
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mistakes on method, results confusion, and poor descriptions using inaccurate terminology."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Methods and results are described, demonstrated and tested throughout, and methods tried by pupils with results gathered and analysed. Repeated review of results occurs throughout the lesson, and methods and results are applied to novel questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.351997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dna-codes-features-rather-processes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That all DNA codes for features rather than processes that are shared by all living organisms; also that animals are the only living organism that have DNA."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make the role of DNA in features and processes explicit, using non-animal examples. Re-iterate the common processes of living organisms, and therefore why there are similarities in the genome."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352023Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-think-light-energy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is a common misconception to think that light (or energy) is a substance and a chemical reactant in photosynthesis that is converted into glucose."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The role of light in transferring energy to chlorophyll for photosynthesis is explored."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dominant-condition-stronger-strongest-characteristic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A dominant condition is 'stronger' and that only the strongest characteristic is inherited from one parent."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Two genes are inherited, so both alleles contribute to the genotype. In some cases one is dominant and therefore will always be expressed (through protein structure) in the phenotype, the recessive allele is still present."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352052Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-viruses-alive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may believe that viruses are alive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Viruses are not cells. They do not carry out many of the processes of living organisms such as replication and respiration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352109Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-heart-its-own-blood-vessels
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The heart does not have its own blood vessels. Students often believe the heart gets oxygen and glucose from the blood circulating through it."""@en ;
  curric:correction "The heart has its own blood supply through the coronary arteries."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hiv-aids-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "HIV and AIDS are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction "HIV is the virus and AIDS is a consequence of late-stage HIV infection."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-hormones-body-form
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that all hormones in the body form part of the reproductive system and its regulation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The slide deck gives specific examples of hormones that are not part of the reproductive system; this includes the example of antagonistic hormones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352197Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mistakes-definitions-diffusion-osmosis-active
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mistakes with the definitions of diffusion, osmosis and active transport are common, as are their application to biological scenarios."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The definitions are clearly stated and contextualised using key human biological processes and examples."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-scientific-drawings-made-using-microscope
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Scientific drawings made using a microscope are difficult to do and often sketched like an artwork. The requirements are clear and precise and require practise to get right."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The expectations for scientific drawings are clearly stated and shown visually. Opportunities to practise drawing different structures are included throughout the lesson."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.352231Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-acid-rain-immediately-harmful-human
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Acid rain is immediately harmful to human skin. Acid rain's effects are quick and devastating."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Educate that acid rain is less acidic than household acids. Discuss the long-term ecological and structural impacts of acid rain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.354239Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-mass-weight-object
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils confuse the mass or weight of an object with density."@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide pupils with a range of objects of varying sizes they are going to measure the density of and, before starting to do so, ask the pupils to rank the objects in order of density with explanations. Compare results to the list after measurements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.354992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-multicellular-specialised-cells-individual
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Only animals are multicellular; that specialised cells are individual; all DNA in a cell is the same so will produce the same proteins."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Examples of multicellular plants, with specialised cells, tissues and organs provided; show images of cells as tissues rather than just individual. All cells have the same DNA, but it is whether the genes are turned on that makes them specialise."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-strand-dna-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that each strand of DNA is the same without recognising one strand is inverted."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The slides specifically mention the second strand is inverted and this is also reinforced using diagrams of inverted nucleotides wherever possible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quadrats-randomly-placed-survey-organisms
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Quadrats must always be randomly placed to survey organisms."@en ;
  curric:correction """Quadrats can be systematically placed as part of sampling activities. This is not random sampling but regular sampling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tumours-cancerous-dangerous
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All tumours are cancerous and dangerous."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students are given very clear examples of the difference between benign and malignant tumours. The difference between the two is covered in the slide deck, check for understanding questions and practice tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-organisms-able-quickly-adapt-place
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That organisms are able to quickly adapt to the place where they live."@en ;
  curric:correction """Referring to inheritance, explain that changes to organisms take time to evolve - responses to any environmental change is not instant. In some organisms, where reproduction is slow, responses can be too slow to avoid extinction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356219Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adult-stem-cells-dont-exist
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Adult stem cells don't exist or can differentiate in the same way as embryonic stem cells."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Give examples of adult stem cells and the types of cells they will differentiate into, using examples that pupils might be familiar with."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356240Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-forget-selective-breeding-process
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often forget that selective breeding is a process that happens over many generations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson includes examples of how to describe the process of selective breeding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356330Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recognising-difference-images-interphase-prophase
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Recognising the difference between images of interphase and prophase. In particular, the idea of DNA condensing to form visible chromosomes during prophase."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are two slides that aim to show the difference between DNA held within the nucleus and visible chromosomes where DNA has condensed. There is also a check for understanding question and practise task question to reinforce this concept."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356337Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-decomposers-release-energy-recycled-back
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Decomposers release energy that is recycled back to plants."@en ;
  curric:correction """Decomposers break down dead organisms and waste. This returns minerals to the soil which can be used by plants. It is worth stating that some decomposers are eaten by carnivores as part of food chain diagrams that include decomposers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356558Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recognising-cell-growth-dna-condenses
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Recognising that after cell growth DNA condenses to form visible chromosomes and the nuclear membrane breaks down."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are slides that aim to show the difference between DNA held within the nucleus and visible chromosomes where DNA has condensed. There is also a check for understanding question and practice task question to reinforce this concept."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356674Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-varying-population-size-organism-affect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Varying the population size of an organism will not affect an ecosystem."@en ;
  curric:correction """All organisms are important within an ecosystem. If one organism's population size changes, either as a result of a biotic factor (predation / disease) or an abiotic factor, it will affect all organisms within the ecosystem (to varying degrees)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356679Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-struggle-understand-concept-common
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often struggle to understand the concept of having a common ancestor and confuse it with one species being descended from another."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson uses evolutionary trees to help students visualise the relationships between groups of organisms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-animals-choose-adapt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that animals choose to adapt themselves to their environment."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The language in this lesson has been specifically chosen to avoid embedding this misconception and CfUs help expose this misconception in student thinking."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-tumours-cancerous-dangerous
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that all tumours are cancerous and dangerous."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pupils are given very clear examples of the difference between benign and malignant tumours. The difference between the two is covered in the slide deck, check for understanding questions and practice tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356920Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-struggle-remember-organism-animals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often struggle to remember that any organism (not just animals) can become a fossil"""@en ;
  curric:correction """This is addressed in the lesson by including examples of fossilised plant and cell material. The first practice task also addresses this misconception."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stem-cells-treat-diseases-proved
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That stem cells can treat more diseases than they have been proved to. All stem cells used are taken from embryos."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Introducing the idea of induced stem cells and adult stem cells in treatments, but also that the main use is in research rather than full treatment of a disease or condition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.356939Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quadrats-used-give-accurate-picture
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Quadrats can be used to give an accurate picture of a habitat or ecosystem."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sampling using a quadrat provides only a snapshot of a specific area at a specific time. To give a more accurate understanding, quadrat samples should be taken over a long period to provide a fuller picture of a habitat or ecosystem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.357108Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-knowing-differences-mitosis-meiosis-particular
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Knowing the differences between mitosis and meiosis. In particular when they are used, the number of cell divisions and if variation is present."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The final learning cycle of the lesson serves to compare the features of mitosis and meiosis, this includes CFU questions and a practice task."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.357249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-roots-tissue-plant-contain-living
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Roots are not a tissue of the plant, or contain living cells, also that wood is not made of living cells."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show the cells of roots and how they divide to allow the length and width of the root to grow; also the rings on trees that indicate new cell division in the trunk of a tree."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.357275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-many-pupils-believe-halving-distance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Many pupils will believe that by halving the distance from a light source, the light intensity will double."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As a result of light travelling in all directions, this aspect needs to be thought of in terms of area (two dimensions). The lesson takes pupils through an example which demonstrates how light intensity is proportional to the square of the distance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.358154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-small-increase-greenhouse
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception is that a small increase in greenhouse gases and a small rise in Earth's temperature will not have much impact on organisms on Earth beyond polar ice melting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson outlines how human activities increase the concentration of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere and how this links to climate change. The lesson also outlines how climate change impacts life on Earth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.358284Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-daughter-cells-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that daughter cells have different DNA to the parent cell."@en ;
  curric:correction """Slides repeatedly address the concept that DNA is copied and that daughter cells are genetically identical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.358357Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-excessive-growth-plants
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception is that the excessive growth of the plants in eutrophication is the cause of a reduction in biodiversity as a result of the plants using up the oxygen in the water."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Steps in eutrophication are outlined. Increased minerals cause the growth of plants at the surface resulting in the death and decomposition of the plants. Decomposing dead organic matter results in micro-organisms using oxygen and biodiversity loss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.358522Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-heating-substance-strongly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes think that heating a substance strongly and for extended periods will improve the quality of separation via distillation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress that distillation is a skill which requires careful control of heating so only one substance is in the condenser at a time. Understanding the link between application of heat to the mixture, boiling point and reading a thermometer is essential"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.359848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-observing-excess-metal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often do not understand that observing excess metal oxide in the reaction mixture means that the acid has fully reacted."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise how to observe the end of the reaction and what these observations mean, i.e. excess metal oxide in the reaction mixture or using pH paper to indicate the solution is neutral. Both are evidence of the acid having fully reacted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361813Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-air-resistance-increases
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may believe that as air resistance increases, a falling object decelerates (slows down)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Analyse footage of a falling object played back in slow motion, or frame–by–frame, to show that the speed of a falling object increases, up to a maximum speed, and at no time does it slow down."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361818Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ionic-bond-transfer-electrons-electrostatic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The ionic bond is the transfer of electrons and not the electrostatic forces of attraction between the ions. Dot and cross diagrams show the empirical formula of the lattice and not an ionic molecule."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure students have a good understanding of how ions are formed, the arrangement of ions in a giant lattice structure and empricial formula before moving on to disucss using dot and cross diagrams to model ionic bonding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-light-rays-actual
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that light rays are actual physical things that are the constituents of light."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It needs to be made explicit through teaching that light rays are imaginary lines that show the direction in which light is travelling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-coordinating-measurements-sugar-solution-practical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Coordinating the measurements and the sugar solution in this practical is fiddly and if not done methodically, the results can be easily confused."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The table in which results will be recorded is clearly labelled and used, and a copy is provided in the worksheet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-gradient-v-graph-equal-1
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The gradient of an I-V graph is equal to 1/R because I = V ÷ R."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain how the equation for a straight line graph y = mx + c does not apply in this case because the graph is not a straight line."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361843Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enzymes-die-rather-denature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Enzymes die rather than denature."@en ;
  curric:correction """The word denature is clearly introduced and a CfU explores the word die vs denature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-many-pupils-uncertain-forces-attracting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Many pupils are uncertain about the forces attracting or repelling particles inside an atom."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Extend explanations to include electrostatic forces between protons in the nucleus and introduce the strong nuclear force to explain why nuclei do not self destruct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361853Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-equilibrium-occur-open-system-reactions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Equilibrium can occur in an open system; no reactions occur at equilibrium; amounts of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Equilibrium requires a closed system; in an open system, matter exchange disrupts balance. At equilibrium, reactions still occur but at equal rates, leading to constant amounts, not necessarily equal amounts of reactants and products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361858Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animal-cells-same-model-animal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All animal cells are the same as the model animal cell. Energy is created during respiration."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The model animal cell simplifies the complex structure of animal cells. There are specialised animal cells that have different shapes and sub-cellular structures to help them carry out a specific function. Energy is transferred through respiration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-palisade-cell-specialised-cell-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A palisade cell is not a specialised cell as it is used as the plant cell model. All plant cells contain chloroplasts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Presentation outlines that the palisade cell is a specialised cell. Question in the check for understanding that is designed to show chloroplasts are not in root hair cells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361890Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-covalent-bonds-break-simple-molecules
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Covalent bonds break in simple molecules for substances to melt/boil, because this happens in giant covalent structures."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight that bonds require large amounts of energy to break, hence the very high melting points of diamond and graphite. As all atoms are bonded these must be broken to melt/boil."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-cannot-apply-main-v
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often cannot apply the main I–V graphs to similar components."@en ;
  curric:correction """Describe how the p.d. and current in components behaves to draw out similarities that can be used to describe unfamiliar components."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-temperature-increasing-e
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can often think that when the temperature is not increasing, i.e. at a change of state, that the experiment is 'not working'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Question students whilst circulating the class about what they would expect to see and try to get them to imagine what is happening to the particles. Use the heating curve to explain why the temperature did not increase during state changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-many-pupils-believe-order-determine
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Many pupils believe that in order to determine a population size within a habitat, all organisms within a habitat have to be counted."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Populations can be estimated using sampling techniques. As long as a sample size is large enough, it will provide a reliable estimate of the population size. Pupils should understand that counting all individuals in a habitat is very difficult to do."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361916Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-funnel-same-filter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A funnel is the same as a filter."@en ;
  curric:correction """A funnel streamlines movement, while a filter separates materials. Use everyday examples to highlight the difference, e.g. an oil funnel vs. an oil filter, or a coffee funnel vs. a coffee filter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-challenging-think-current
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils find it challenging to think about how current flows through the connections and around the coil in the motor."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Take pupils step–by–step through the building of a motor from a motor kit and provide an opportunity for pupils to build their own working motor to help them to consolidate their understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.361926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-battery-pushes-constant-current-around
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A battery pushes a constant current around a circuit."@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunity for pupils to measure p.d. across a power supply when the resistance of a circuit it is connected to is altered."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362363Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-trolley-released-speeds-quickly-start
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When the trolley is released, it speeds up quickly at the start and then rolls at a constant speed."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show a video of an accelerating trolley in slow motion identifying the distance travelled in successive equal intervals of time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362371Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pair-coordinates-s-t-graph
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A pair of coordinates on a s-t graph can be used to calculate the instantaneous speed or velocity at that point, but that only works for a straight line graph through the origin."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask pupils to calculate the velocity of a graph that represents a steady velocity on a line that does not go through the origin, and to check to see if dividing the values at any point on the line gives the right value for velocity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362405Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-small-organisms-plants-dont-respire
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That small organisms and plants don't respire (only humans and other large animals)."""@en ;
  curric:correction "This lesson demonstrates experimentally that small organisms respire."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362597Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-atoms-react-because-want-gain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Atoms react because they 'want' to gain a fuller outer shell of electrons – atoms don't have feelings! Monatomic means one atom and may be confused with the term element, which means one type of atom."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Take care with language and avoid personifying the atoms. Make sure that definitions and terms are used correctly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362624Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-atmosphere-made-mainly-oxygen-carbon
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The atmosphere is made up of mainly oxygen and carbon dioxide."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that Earth's atmosphere is delicately balanced. There is enough oxygen to maintain life, and enough carbon dioxide to help insulate the planet, maintaining the temperature that allows life to exist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362638Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-heating-mixture-strongly-cause-distillation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Heating a mixture strongly will cause distillation to occur more quickly."@en ;
  curric:correction """Heating a mixture strongly could cause multiple components to enter a condenser (or delivery tube), resulting in a contaminated distillate. Careful, gentle heating of the mixture to ensure no bubbles near the condenser will reduce contamination."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362646Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mistakes-calculations-surface-area-volume
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mistakes with the calculations of surface area or volume are common. The concepts of surface area, volume and their ratio, with the effect that changing these have on diffusion, are difficult."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Plenty of practise on how to calculate surface area and volume, and compare these as a ratio, some simplified, is included. The experiment results are used to show the impact of changing surface area, volume and width on diffusion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mistakes-around-calculating-change-percentage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mistakes around calculating change in percentage mass are common, as are misunderstandings around why changes in mass occur."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The calculations for percentage mass are introduced and walked through with an 'I-do, we-do, you-do' model. There are plenty of calculations to practice on. Why mass changes occur is also covered in detail and with supporting diagrams."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-magnetic-field-effects-mistaken-electric
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Magnetic field effects are often mistaken for electric field effects."@en ;
  curric:correction """Be explicit in teaching that electric charges and charged objects are not magnetic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362661Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understanding-moving-particular-speed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often do not have an understanding of what moving at a particular speed means in the real world, and treat answers as ‘just numbers’."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use real world examples of speeds through examples and questions asked (N.B. 10 m/s is approximately 20 miles per hour)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362668Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-solve-circuits-need-put-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To solve circuits you need only to put numbers into equations."@en ;
  curric:correction """Talk through circuits with pupils before analysing them in order to develop an intrinsic understanding of how circuits work; research shows this improves pupils’ problem solving ability for electric circuits."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-circuits-analysed-sequentially-starting-battery
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Circuits are analysed sequentially, starting at the battery and working round, one component at a time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask questions that prompt pupils to consider the effect of changes to one component on the whole circuit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362913Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-consider-time-acceleration-equation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often consider time in the acceleration equation to be moment in time (perhaps read from a graph) rather than a change in time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Label the value of t in the acceleration as a change of time rather than just time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.362925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-ideas-bonds-require
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse the ideas that bonds require energy to break i.e. endothermic process and that energy is released forming bonds i.e. exothermic process."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Bonds will not break unless energy is absorbed to do so. The formation of a bond releases energy to the surroundings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363178Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-atoms-anthropomorphised-described-wanting-full
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Atoms are often anthropomorphised, described as 'wanting' full shells. This implies intent and oversimplifies chemical bonding."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on the tendency of atoms to fill their outer shell to 8 electrons to become stable. Emphasise carbon atoms do this by sharing electrons in covalent bonds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-terms-current-voltage-resistance-energy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The terms current, voltage, resistance, energy and power, together with the properties of each, are often mixed up."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As each term is introduced during this lesson, spend a few moments checking pupils’ understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363213Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-displacement-distance-graph-picture-wave
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A displacement-distance graph is a picture of a wave, with 1:1 vertical and horizontal scaling."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Interpret and sketch graphs of waves that are compared to pictures of each wave."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363219Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-clear-magnetic-field-around-conducting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is not clear how the magnetic field around a conducting wire interacts with a uniform magnetic field."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on observing and predicting the direction that a conducting wire is forced in by a uniform magnetic field, and openly admit that explaining this in terms of how the magnetic field interact is too challenging to include in the syllabus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mistakes-made-preparing-practical-instance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mistakes are often made when preparing the practical, for instance which samples go into which test tubes, or carrying out the practical, such as exactly when to take the continuous sample."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The correct approach to preparing and completing this method accurately and carefully is discussed throughout, with quick checks at key points and the opportunity to try it for themselves."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363402Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-including-bonds-either-side-repeating
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Not including the bonds either side of the repeating unit."@en ;
  curric:correction """The slide deck states the need for open bonds to show how repeating units are bonded to each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363455Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dynamic-equilibrium-reactions-stop-increasing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """At dynamic equilibrium the reactions stop; increasing pressure always shifts equilibrium to one side; increasing temperature always favours product formation; catalysts shift the equilibrium position."""@en ;
  curric:correction """At dynamic equilibrium, reactions continue at equal rates. Pressure shifts equilibrium only if gas molecule numbers differ. Temperature favours the endothermic direction when increased. Catalysts speed up reaching equilibrium but don't shift it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363465Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-atomic-number-mass
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse the atomic number and mass number with regard to the number of electrons in an atom. They also can confuse the number of electrons which can be held by each shell."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that the lower number (atomic number/proton number) represents the number of electrons (reference to the mass being larger can help). Practise as many electron arrangements as possible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363474Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-distance-two-crests-oscilloscope-graph
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The distance between two crests of an oscilloscope graph is equal to one wavelength."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the need to read scales of graphs first and that the horizontal scale of an oscilloscope graph is time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.363480Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-compare-accelerations-objects-basis
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may compare the accelerations of objects on the basis of final velocities and may fail to take into account the time interval over which the change in velocity occurred."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide pupils with opportunity to analyse measurements of changes in velocity in which the starting velocities vary. A pair of light gates at two positions along the ramp will allow this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475363Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-understanding-electrical-circuits-memorising-equations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Understanding electrical circuits is about memorising equations and procedures."@en ;
  curric:correction """Give pupils the opportunity to discuss what happens in a circuit before they attempt to answer questions about it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-solve-circuit-problems-need-put
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To solve circuit problems you need only to put numbers into equations."@en ;
  curric:correction """Talk through circuits with pupils before analysing them in order to develop an intrinsic understanding of how circuits work; research shows this improves pupils’ problem solving ability for electric circuits."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475432Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-calculating-energy-elastic-store-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When calculating energy in the elastic store, pupils often work out (½ times spring constant tmes extension) and then square everything, rather than just the extension."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scaffold calculations to show how elastic energy is calculated, taking pupils through how to do this on their calculators without making a mistake."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475540Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-use-terms-power-energy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often use the terms power and energy interchangeably."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use concrete examples to show pupils that a greater power transfers energy more quickly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475557Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-rote-learn-specific-examples
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes rote-learn what specific examples of refraction look like, rather than developing a more general understanding of the direction waves turn based on changes in wave speed."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Teach pupils the general theory of refraction and apply it to a variety of different examples where wave speed changes (e.g. sound waves refract in the opposite direction to light at an air-glass boundary due to the different wave speeds)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475574Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-v-f-speed-dependent-frequency
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """In, v = f × λ, speed is dependent on frequency and wavelength, rather then the medium."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on speed being property of a medium and equation not being as an equation with three interdependent variables."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475869Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-forget-include-thinking-distance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often forget to include thinking distance in the overall stopping distance, or imagine that thinking distance is too short to matter."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model a situation in which a child steps out from behind a parked car 10 m in front of a driver. At 20 mph the thinking distance is about 6 m and braking distance 6 m; at 30 mph these are 9 m and 14 m."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.475881Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-particles-longitudinal-wave-move-forward
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Particles in a longitudinal wave move forward and backward between one compression and the next."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Demonstrate the movement of a candle flame in front of a loudspeaker set to a very low frequency with a wavelength of about 30 m (at 10 Hz)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.476302Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dna-living-necessarily-chemical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "DNA is living and not necessarily a chemical."@en ;
  curric:correction """Discussing that DNA is a chemical molecule and showing how it is made up of smaller chemical groups, and then modelling this chemical structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.476433Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ph-increases-optimum-enzymes-denature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """As pH increases above the optimum, enzymes denature and reaction rate falls, but this is not what happens at pHs below the optimum, so the graph and explanation resemble temperature."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The process of denaturing an enzyme is explored in detail, and a graph of reaction rate is explained carefully to make it clear that the changes to rate occur above and below the optimum pH."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.476444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-realise-resistance-wire-varies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may not realise that the resistance of a wire varies with temperature."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure pupils are aware that the temperature of a metal wire does affect resistance and that precautions should be taken to avoid a temperature change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.476876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-read-volume-gas-incorrectly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often read the volume of gas incorrectly as they do not measure it from the bottom of the meniscus of the water in the measuring cylinder."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson contains a detailed explanation of how to correctly measure volumes from the meniscus, and why this is important."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.476950Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-heat-substance-flows-insulator
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Heat is a substance that flows through an insulator."@en ;
  curric:correction """Always refer to it being particle vibrations that are passed on through a material and do not refer to heat moving."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.476976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-gamete-two-alleles-punnett-square
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A gamete has two alleles, Punnett square has too many alleles for gametes. Also that only four offspring are produced and therefore each will definitely have the genotype and phenotype shown."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model the alleles within gametes so it is clear. Refer to half the gametes having each version, moving away from the idea of divisions of 4."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.476991Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pressure-particular-depth-depends-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The pressure at a particular depth depends on the shape of the container the liquid is in."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Demonstrate different shaped containers with the same depth of water in each and an identical shaped hole 1 cm above the base of each. Identical sized jets of water should shoot out of each hole as the pressure at each hole is (initially) the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plants-absorb-nitrogen-atmosphere-animals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That plants absorb nitrogen from the atmosphere, and animals do not need plants to obtain carbon, so plants are not necessary for food."""@en ;
  curric:correction """How plants obtain carbon and nitrogen, and the reliance that consumers have on producers for these inorganic elements is covered in detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-incorrectly-thinking-use-damage-forests
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Incorrectly thinking that we can use and damage forests and oceans without negative consequences for the planet and our own survival."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson explores the crucial role of forests and oceans as global carbon sinks that offset human carbon emissions, and the impacts of deforestation, global warming and ocean acidification."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477023Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-fail-understand-water-enters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If students fail to understand that water only enters the plant at the roots, and not through the leaves, then the process of transpiration will be very muddled and confused."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson reinforces the pathway that water takes through the plant, clearly stating that water enters at the roots, and showing several times how it moves up through xylem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-plants-dont-respire
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students sometimes think that plants don't respire, and that they (only) photosynthesise instead."""@en ;
  curric:correction "This lesson contains examples of plants respiring."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-conservation-biodiversity-happen-large-scale
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The conservation of biodiversity can only happen on a large scale, e.g. through protecting large areas of habitat."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Biodiversity conservation can take place on a small scale, for example, by providing habitats in gardens and in urban areas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477070Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ozone-layer-climate-change-linked
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Ozone layer and climate change are linked/the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ozone layer depletion was caused by human activity, but not through use of burning fossil fuels/greenhouse gas emissions. Both are atmospheric issues, but not the same issue."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477133Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-mix-atomic-number-atomic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often mix up the atomic number and atomic mass number and get confused over which subatomic particles these represent."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It helps to describe the atomic number as the proton number to help the pupils remember. Also, the provided periodic tables often have a key to help and this should be highlight to pupils."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477143Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mmr-vaccination-causes-autism
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The MMR vaccination causes autism."@en ;
  curric:correction """The study by Dr Wakefield is highly flawed, and has been discredited. Many subsequent studies have found no link between the MMR vaccination and autism. Measles is a highly infectious disease that can have devastating consequences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.477477Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-frequently-write-exams-respiration
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students frequently write in exams that respiration \"creates\" energy."@en ;
  curric:correction "This lesson contains checks and practice tasks that address this misconception."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.478018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mixing-scientific-terms-such-antigen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mixing up scientific terms such as antigen and antibody."@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores the relationship and differences between antigens, antibodies and antitoxins."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.478146Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-plants-stomata-equal-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thinking that plants have stomata in equal numbers on every surface of their leaves."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Through practical work and data analysis, pupils explore the distribution of stomata on the top and bottom surfaces of leaves."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.478250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-blood-cells-protect-us-against
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All blood cells protect us against pathogens."@en ;
  curric:correction """White blood cells are part of the immune system that protects us against pathogens. Red blood cells transport oxygen to cells. Platelets are not cells, but they do help to protect against pathogens by helping to seal wounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.478260Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-digital-ammeters-accurate-smallest-amount
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Digital ammeters are always accurate to the smallest amount they display."@en ;
  curric:correction """Show pupils a copy of the specifications of the ammeters they are using that show how accurate they really are."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.478664Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-antibodies-remain-blood-years-makes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Antibodies remain in the blood for years, which makes a person immune to a disease."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Antibodies don't stay in the body longer term, the memory cells do and they provide long lasting immunity against a pathogen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.479058Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-water-cycle-includes-processes-evaporation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The water cycle only includes the processes of evaporation from the Earth's surface to the atmosphere and condensation returning water to the Earth."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There is exemplification of how the water cycle involves percolation of water into the ground and how plants use this water. Some of this is released by transpiration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.479102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-velocity-object-same-direction-resultant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The velocity of an object must be in the same direction as the resultant force acting on the object."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Invite pupils to consider situations in which the resultant force is not in the same direction as the velocity, such as an object that has been thrown upwards and is slowing down as its height increases."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.479382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-bigger-spring-constant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think the bigger the spring constant, the more a spring stretches for a given force."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities for pupils to apply understanding that the spring constant describes the stiffness of a spring. The bigger the spring constant, the harder it is to stretch (or compress) the spring."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.479973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-enzyme-act-many-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Thinking that each enzyme can act on many different substrates."@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson reinforces understanding that each enzyme has a specific substrate, because only that substrate will fit into they enzyme's active site."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.479997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-estimating-risks-genetic-engineering-genetically
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Over-estimating the risks of genetic engineering and genetically modified (GM) organisms."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores the need to weigh up possible benefits, risks and ethical questions when making decisions about genetic engineering."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.480008Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-number-one-mole-represents-difficult
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The number one mole represents can be difficult for pupils to grasp and appreciate."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show many real world examples of 6.02 × 10²³ examples of something - that many basketballs would form a planet the size of the Earth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.482050Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-incorrectly-calculating-total-magnification-adding
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Incorrectly calculating the total magnification by adding the magnification of the eyepiece lens to the magnification of the objective lens."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The correct way to calculate the total magnification (by multiplying the magnification of the eyepiece lens by the magnification of the objective lens) is practiced."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.483245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-chemical-formulae-changed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils sometimes think that chemical formulae can be changed to balance atoms."@en ;
  curric:correction """Put boxes around each formula in the equation / pretend there is a bucket of pre-made molecules which they can use to balance the number of atoms on each side.  Stress that it takes perseverance and practice before equations are balanced."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485251Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-infrared-radiation-visible-seen-objects
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Infrared radiation is visible and is seen when objects glow."@en ;
  curric:correction """Distinguish clearly between light radiation and infrared radiation in terms of what is visible and what is not visible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485261Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-amount-energy-gravitational
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that the amount of energy in the gravitational store depends on the path taken by an object to change its height, or the speed of an object at a particular height."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Teaching should include examples of objects increasing height by the same amount by different routes, and examples of objects at the same height moving at different speeds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485347Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-industrial-activities-contribute-atmospheric-pollution
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Only industrial activities contribute to atmospheric pollution. Atmospheric pollutants are always visible."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss natural sources of pollutants, like volcanoes. Explain that many harmful pollutants are invisible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485524Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-water-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All water is the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """The dissolved solid content of water samples is affected by the environment from which it was obtained."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485557Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-many-students-think-mantle-liquid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Many students think the mantle is liquid or semi-liquid. Some think it contains soil or water."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The mantle is almost all solid rock. Less than 1% of it is liquid e.g. at spreading plate boundaries, subduction zones and hot-spots."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485566Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-material-exposed-radiation-become-radioactive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A material exposed to radiation will become radioactive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Take time to clearly distinguish between radioactive contamination and irradiation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485584Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-molecules-substance-change-substance-melts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The molecules of a substance change when a substance melts or break down into individual atoms when it boils."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunity for pupils to describe, in their own words, the effect on particles of the melting and boiling processes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485742Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-models-order-conceived-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Confusion between the models and the order in which they were conceived. Also, pupils often mix up which subatomic particles are present in each model."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Practise is required listing the key features of each model and the subatomic particles present. A timeline with the key features present helps pupils to understand the process of discovery and how long this can take."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485963Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-different-kinds-em-radiation-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The different 'kinds' of EM radiation are different phenomena to each other and to visible light. Pupils may also think all radiation is dangerous, none is natural and that light is not radiation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Each 'kind' of EM radiation is the same phenomena as light (i.e. waves/ripples in electric and magnetic fields) just with different frequencies and wavelengths. Try to refer to different frequencies/frequency ranges rather than different 'kinds'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485980Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-increasing-temperature-increases-rate-product
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Increasing the temperature increases the rate product is formed, and therefore think a faster reaction produces more product."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Increasing the temperature will make the reaction proceed faster but will not change the amount of product formed. The reactants are the limiting factor, not the temperature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-understand-taking-place
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils struggle to understand what is taking place at the horizontal parts of the graph."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Be concise with your language and ask pupils to use the same language. 'have enough energy to overcome the forces of attraction between particles', 'to slide past each other', 'to move past each other'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.485997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-energy-temperature-therefore
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse energy with temperature and therefore expect the products to be higher than the reactants for exothermic reactions i.e. due to temperature increase, and lower for endothermic."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is useful to discuss the energy transfers occurring during the reaction e.g. exothermic reactions involve the reactant's chemical energy store converting to a smaller chemical energy store in the products and a thermal energy store."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-periodic-table-devised
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often believe that the when the periodic table was devised, scientists knew about the subatomic particles."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise when the subatomic particles were discovered in comparison to when Mendeleev devised his periodic table."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adding-bung-top-conical-flask
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Adding a bung to the top of a conical flask does not affect volume measurements."@en ;
  curric:correction """The bung can displace a small volume of gas, which can affect the accuracy of the measurements. It is essential to account for the volume displaced by the bung in calculations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-difficulty-truly-understanding-randomness
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Most pupils have difficulty in truly understanding randomness."@en ;
  curric:correction "Use analogies to explain randomness."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486078Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ionic-substances-binary-compounds-bonding
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Ionic substances are binary compounds. Bonding and structure are the same thing. Only bonding influences properties."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As well as multiple ions in ionic substances, there can be polyatomic ions too. Bonding informs structure, and bonding and structure together influences properties."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486143Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hormones-released-brain-control-mood
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hormones are only released in the brain and control the mood."@en ;
  curric:correction """Hormones control many processes in the body and are secreted from many glands. Those involved in puberty and the menstrual cycle have physical effects that may also impact on mood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusing-electrodes-electrical-cables-carbon
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """confusing the electrodes, electrical cables or carbon electrodes having a break in them"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the PANIC acronym; positive anode negative is cathode. Check all components of the electric circuit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486443Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ivf-highly-effective-without-side
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """IVF is highly effective without side effects. People can already choose the features of a baby. All people can have IVF from the NHS."""@en ;
  curric:correction """IVF is less than 40% effective and this decreases with the age of the mother over 35. Genetic testing of embryos can be used to look for a disease, but genes cannot be altered. There is criteria for receiving IVF from the NHS and it is limited."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486473Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-measure-final-temperature-reaction
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often measure the final temperature of the reaction mixture rather than the highest temperature."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage pupils to keep monitoring the temperature until it starts to decrease; that way they will know they have seen the highest temperature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486573Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-get-confused-transport-xylem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students get confused between transport in the xylem (water and minerals) and the phloem (sugars)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """These sections are covered in separate lessons, each with clear explanations and reinforcing tasks to support learning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486595Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-acids-eat-substances
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often believe that acids 'eat' away at substances, e.g. acid rain and limestone, rather than understanding that this is a chemical reaction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Using familiar reactions between acids and bases, e.g. hydrochloric acid and sodium hydroxide or calcium carbonate, will provide evidence that a reaction has taken place (i.e. a change in temperature or producing a gas)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-appreciate-difference-using-inert
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils do not always appreciate the difference between using inert carbon electrodes and metal electrodes, which will take part in the reaction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide pupils with the opportunity to investigate the electrolysis of copper sulfate with both inert electrodes and with copper electrodes and then compare the results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486621Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-wastewater-same-sewage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some pupils think that 'wastewater' is the same as 'sewage' and/or that anything found in a sewer is 'sewage'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress that wastewater is any used water that has been affected by domestic, industrial and agricultural processes; sewage is a part of waste water, but specifically that which is contaminated by with faeces and urine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486633Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-particles-within-liquid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that the particles within the liquid will have melted or boiled rather than remain the same size and shape, i.e. atoms do not have bulk properties like melting and boiling points."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that you specifically say that the particles themselves will not melt or boil."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486642Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cracking-same-fractional-distillation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Cracking is the same as fractional distillation."@en ;
  curric:correction """Fractional distillation separates hydrocarbons based on their boiling points. Cracking alters the molecular formula of compounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486663Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-able-explain-set-potometer-difficult
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Being able to explain the set up of a potometer is difficult because it has so many stages that are tricky."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The stages of setting up a potometer are broken down into four parts, checked for understanding, reinforced with a lab demonstration video and concluded with a cartoon task."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486707Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-concentration-solution-excess-changes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thinking that as the concentration of a solution in excess changes, so does the volume of gas produced."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The slide deck uses graphical data to show that the same volume of gas is produced when different concentrations are used, so long as the reacting solution is in excess."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486740Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-find-difficult-understand-why
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students find it difficult to understand why continuous removal of ammonia is required to increase yield."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight that the Haber Process is a dynamic equilibrium. If ammonia is not continuously removed, the equilibrium will shift back towards the reactants, reducing the yield."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486758Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-link-chemical-formulae
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can struggle to link chemical formulae to what is happening on the atomic level and to what they observe during a chemical reaction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce via demonstrations, modelling and diagrams via Johnstone's triangle.  One simple demo (e.g. magnesium + oxygen) = one model, one diagram and one chemical reaction equation.  Use progressively more complicated demos and build up from there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486831Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-interpret-information-contains
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can struggle to interpret information that contains several samples on one chromatogram."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress a systematic approach to interpreting chromatograms (i.e. use rulers). Live modelling this using a visualiser helps enormously."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-substances-need-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils think that substances need to be at their boiling point temperature to evaporate."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use plenty of real life examples of liquids evaporating in situations where pupils know that the liquid is not above its boiling point but still evaporates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-applying-equation-f-m-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When applying the equation F = m × a, pupils may take F to be any one of the forces acting on the object, rather than specifically the resultant force."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide some more complex examples, in which forces act in opposite directions, so pupils are required to work out the resultant force in preparation for completing calculations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486923Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-v-f-x-speed-dependent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """In, v = f x λ, speed is dependent on frequency and wavelength, rather than the medium."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on speed being property of a medium and equation not being as an equation with three interdependent variables."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.486992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-belief-resultant-force-needed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common belief is that a resultant force is needed to keep an object in motion, and if no resultant force acts on an object then it must be stationary."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss examples in which friction is very low or absent, such as a puck sliding across an ice rink or an object being dropped during a space walk and extrapolate to what would happen if friction disappeared entirely."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487001Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-tendency-believe-velocity-positive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often have a tendency to believe that a velocity must have a positive value and have difficulty in associating a reverse in direction with a change in sign."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is important to make sure pupils are secure in their knowledge of the vector–scalar distinction; use plenty of visual examples."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-gas-state-thinking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils to understand gas state; thinking solids, liquids and gases as 'types' of matter."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Refer to/use particle models to help clarify different states of matter and use these to describe why separation techniques work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487027Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-multicellular-organisms-reproduce-cell-division
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Multicellular organisms reproduce by cell division like unicellular organisms."@en ;
  curric:correction """Multicellular organisms use cell division for reproduction. A non-example will be used to show reproduction is not part of reproduction in multicellular organisms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487043Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-metal-individual-atom-property-metal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A metal is an individual atom. The property of a metal atom is the same as the bulk material. Pupils get confused between the attractive forces in the metal atoms and the metallic bond."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce the idea that atoms are tiny and not visible to the naked eye. The material we know as metal is many millions of atoms joined together. Revisit the structure of the atoms before introducing the idea of metallic bonding and giant structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487052Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-make-mistakes-identifying-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often make mistakes when identifying the different types of bonds and the number of each in a molecule. They may also reverse the calculation of the overall energy change, as make - break."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Molecules can be complex and should be drawn to show all the bonds. Emphasis that double and triple covalent bonds are different to single bonds. Pupils should be instructed to consider whether a reaction is exothermic or endothermic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487069Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-identify-surroundings-exothermic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils struggle to identify the surroundings in exothermic and endothermic reactions and why the temperature decreases in endothermic reactions when energy is transferred into the reaction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the surroundings are where you are making the temperature measurements and that the energy is transferred from the thermal energy store of the surroundings to the chemical energy store of the reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487094Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-understand-using-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes struggle to understand how using different mobile and/or stationary phases affects the resulting chromatograms."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Perform chromatography of the same mixture using different mobile phases/stationary phases and discuss the pros/cons of each combination."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487184Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-accept-objects-left-room
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often do not accept that all objects left in a room for a long time are the same temperature."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities to consolidate the understanding that particles vibrating with more energy transfer some of that energy to particles with less energy through collisions and when bonded together in a solid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487270Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-displacement-time-graph-picture-wave
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A displacement-time graph is a picture of a wave."@en ;
  curric:correction """Interpret and sketch displacement-time graphs of waves that are compared to descriptions of each wave."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487354Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-reaction-stops-x-longer-visible
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The reaction stops when the 'X' is no longer visible."@en ;
  curric:correction """The disappearance of the cross only indicates that the sulfur precipitate has formed sufficiently to obscure the cross. The reaction itself continues beyond this point until all reactants are consumed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487364Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-calculate-instantaneous-rate-reaction-reading
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """To calculate the instantaneous rate of reaction by reading values from the graph at a specific time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Students need to draw a tangent in order to calculate the gradient of the graph at a specific time to work out the instantaneous rate of reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-precise-accurate-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Thinking that precise and accurate are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """It may help to draw a bullseye target board. Precise results will all be close to each other but may not be near the bullseye. Accurate results will be near the bullseye but may be more scattered if they are not precise."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487398Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-many-students-write-organisms-change
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Many students write that organisms change themselves to become better adapted to their environment."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson contains checks for this misconception and challenges it with examples of natural selection explained at the genetic level."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487407Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-allele-increases-risk-disease
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thinking that an allele that increases the risk of a disease makes it certain to happen."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores the idea the alleles can be risk factors for disease, and that in many cases other factors also affect the risk."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487428Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pressure-weight-force-pressure-preferred
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pressure is a weight or a force; and pressure has a preferred downwards direction in a liquid or gas."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the particle model to provide opportunities for pupils to explain the causes of pressure in a gas that is in a container, and to explain how the difference in pressure between inside and outside causes an outward force."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-frequency-wavelength-waves-string-affect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Frequency or wavelength of waves on a string will affect the wave speed."@en ;
  curric:correction """The speed of waves on a string only depends on the properties of the wave medium (the string) e.g. tension, density"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487492Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-realise-energy-transfers-usually
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not realise that energy transfers usually result in the heating of the surroundings and therefore some energy ends up in a thermal store."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Pupils should have opportunity to identify and describe places in a system where energy is dissipated and transferred into a thermal store."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487683Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sound-waves-somehow-sounds-hear
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sound waves somehow “are” the sounds you hear."@en ;
  curric:correction """The sensation of hearing sound (what you hear) is a different thing to what a sound wave is (longitudinal oscillations of particles)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487701Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-carbon-forms-alike
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think all carbon forms are alike, ignoring structure's impact on properties."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise structure-property relationships. Use models to show how diamond's and graphite's differing bonds affect their characteristics."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487732Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-climate-change-leads-hotter-weather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Climate change only leads to hotter weather. Human activity has a negligible impact on climate change."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain the diverse effects of climate change, including extreme weather. Highlight the significant role of human activity in accelerating climate change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.487903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-mistake-same-mass-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils mistake that the same mass of different substances = the same number of particles."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This activity reinforces the mathematical relationship between relative formula mass of a substance, the number of particles present and the mass measured in the lab."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488062Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-many-misconceptions-dna-including
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students have many misconceptions about DNA including, for example, that DNA is alive."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This lesson includes dual coded diagrams of DNA to help avoid embedding misconceptions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488071Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-chemical-definitions-concentration
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse the chemical definitions for 'concentration' and 'strength'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress that concentration is a measure of particles interspersed throughout a specific volume of liquid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488109Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-particles-embedded-substance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that the particles are embedded in the substance rather than being the substance. Most pupils think that substances in the liquid state will compress a little."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce that most substances can exist in all three states of matter and when they are in the gas state there is nothing between the particles but empty space."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488118Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-electrolysis-charge-carriers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that, during electrolysis, the charge carriers are electrons and not ions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Revisit the structure of ionic compounds in the solid and liquid states. Point out that there are no delocalised electrons. The electrons are associated with ions and so are unable to move through the electrolyte. Ions can move in the liquid state."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488536Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-atoms-visible-powerful-optical-microscopes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Atoms are visible under powerful optical microscopes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that atoms are far too small to see and our descriptions of atoms are models, based on evidence, that help us understand how they behave."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488587Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-short-circuit-circuit-doesnt-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A short circuit is a circuit that doesn’t work."@en ;
  curric:correction """Demonstrate several short circuits and provide opportunity for pupils to describe what they are in their own words."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-pupils-misunderstand-links-increased
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is common for pupils to misunderstand the links between increased or decreased body temperature and the impact on enzyme function, and changes in water concentration and cell structure."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explanations of the effect of temperature on enzyme activity, the link between body temperature and enzyme function, and conditions such as hyper- and hypo-thermia are made. The link between water balance, osmosis and cell shapes are also explored."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-struggle-idea-plants-organs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students struggle with the idea that plants have organs and systems like humans, and that all these systems and cells are adapted with specialised features to enable them to do their job effectively."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The plant vascular system and human circulatory system have been compared, and human lung alveoli and digestive system villi have been compared with root hair cells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488761Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-tend-think-water-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils tend to think that all water is the same. Pupils tend to forget that non-visible substances are also found in water."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress that pure water only contains H₂O molecules. Other waters may include varying amounts of dissolved salts, other solids or micro-organisms. Stress that microbes must be killed for water to be potable, but are too difficult to remove."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-water-samples-neutral-e-ph
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All water samples are neutral (i.e. pH of 7)."@en ;
  curric:correction """The acidity / alkalinity of water samples is affected by the dissolved substances in each sample."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488857Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-use-terms-evaporation-boiling
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes use the terms evaporation and boiling interchangeably, but they are not the same."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Boiling: a liquid substance is heated and gas bubbles form. Evaporation: same, BUT only on the surface of the liquid, no bubbles form and the gas mixes with air."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.488875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-easily-confuse-different-types
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils *very* easily confuse different types of reactions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend time developing ways to help pupils remember the differences and regularly challenge them to explain why one reaction is the type it is."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-oxidation-reduction-loss-gain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thinking that oxidation and reduction are only to do with the loss and gain of oxygen."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Oxidation is the loss of electrons or the gain of oxygen. Reduction is the gain of electrons or loss of oxygen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-displacement-time-graphs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often confuse displacement–time graphs with velocity–time graphs."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the need for pupils to always read the axes of a graph first, before they start to think about any lines drawn on it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lcas-measure-carbon-footprint-product
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "LCAs only measure the carbon footprint of a product."@en ;
  curric:correction """The slide deck addresses what is included in a LCA such as energy use, water use and pollutants released."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489306Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-mix-terms-power-force
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often mix up the terms power and force, which are often used interchangeably in everyday speech."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities for pupils to describe events in which the terms need to be used appropriately, for example in lifting two different sized weights (different forces) whilst increasing their energy at the same rate (same power)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489480Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-magnetic-field-poles-magnet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The magnetic field is only at the poles of a magnet."@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunity for pupils to plot magnetic field lines around pairs of bar magnets and to experiment with a second magnet as described in the teacher tip."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-negative-values-displacement-time-graph
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Negative values on a displacement-time graph always represent motion that is backwards."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities for pupils to plot a range of displacement-time graphs in real time in order for them to understand how the graph represents different motions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-terms-force-energy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse the terms force, energy, and work done and use them interchangeably."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities for pupils to describe events in which the three terms need to be used appropriately, e.g. in describing energy transfers for pushing (force) a crate (doing work) along a level surface (energy transferred)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489645Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-calculating-mean-repeat-readings-reduces
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Calculating a mean of repeat readings reduces (random) errors in measurements."@en ;
  curric:correction """Calculating a mean reduces the effect that random errors have on a final result. The random errors in the original readings are unaffected."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-carbon-allotrope-discoveries
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that all carbon allotrope discoveries were recent and that these materials are primarily used in cutting-edge, futuristic applications."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the timeline of discoveries (graphite > fullerenes > nanotubes > graphene), highlighting theoretical predictions preceding isolation. Discuss current uses (e.g. nanotubes in sporting equipment) alongside potential future breakthroughs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-struggle-distinguish-phytomining-bioleaching
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students struggle to distinguish between phytomining and bioleaching."@en ;
  curric:correction "Reinforce that the term 'phyto' is a combining form meaning 'plant'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489727Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-indicators-provide-precise-ph-values
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All indicators provide precise pH values and give the same information as pH meters."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Indicators do not provide exact pH values; they only indicate whether a solution is acidic, neutral, or alkaline by changing colour. A pH meter, on the other hand, measures the exact pH value of a solution and is more accurate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.489785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-covalent-bonds-broken
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that covalent bonds are broken when any covalent structure undergoes a change of state; not just those in giant covalent structures."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use physical models to show the difference between a simple covalent structure and a giant covalent structure. Explain that it is the weak intermolecular forces that are overcome when a simple covalent molecule changes state."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490173Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-regularly-think-neutralisation-produces
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils regularly think that neutralisation produces a neutral (i.e. pH 7) solution."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress that neutralisation occurs from a complete reaction between an acid and base, which usually occurs between strong acids and strong bases.  If a weak acid or weak base is used, the salt solution produced may be alkaline or acidic respectively."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490326Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-pupils-fail-consider-hanging
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is common for pupils to fail to consider the hanging mass as part of the accelerating mass."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that all of the moving parts in the investigation are connected, are accelerated together, and need to be included in the measurement of the mass being accelerated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490335Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-fractional-distillation-produces
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some students may think that fractional distillation produces new substances from crude oil."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is important to emphasise that crude oil is a mixture, and the process of fractional distillation is to separate out the different hydrocarbons based on their boiling points."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recognising-particles-present-aqueous-solution
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Recognising the particles present in an aqueous solution is problematic. Understanding how an electric current flows through an electrolyte is confusing as ions, not electrons, are the charge carrier."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that pupils have a good understanding of key terms such as atom, ion, electron, solutions and reactivity before moving on to the electrolysis of aqueous solutions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490849Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-bacteria-living-organisms
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that bacteria are not living organisms and/or do not evolve. Pupils may also think that all bacteria are harmful."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores two examples of evolution in bacteria, explaining each example through mutation, reproduction and natural selection."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490857Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-modern-classification-system
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the modern classification system that we use today is complete."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils why new data from experiments or observations leads to changes in models or theories."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490878Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-organisms-evolve-short-period-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Organisms evolve over a short period of time."@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw pupils attention to the tome scales on the evolutionary trees to show that evolution takes place slowly over long periods of time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490891Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-misconception-heat-substance-flow
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often have the misconception that heat is a substance that can flow."@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus learning on how heating causes particles to move more quickly, and the effects that this can have on the density of a fluid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.490960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-temperature-ice-0-c-temperature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The temperature of ice is always 0ºC and the temperature of water in the liquid state cannot be 0°C."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make explicit observations that water can be in either or both of the solid and liquid states at 0°C."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-eukaryotic-cells-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think that all eukaryotic cells have the same cell components."@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw pupils' attention to the differences between the different types of eukaryotic cells. Focus on the presence of a nucleus, mitochondria, and, in plant cells, chloroplasts, as identifying characteristics of eukaryotic cells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491210Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-contraceptive-pill-protect-stis-contraception
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The contraceptive pill can protect from STIs; that all contraception is 100% effective; there are no side effects to hormonal contraception."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss barrier methods and their benefit in preventing STIs, oral contraceptive can be affected by user error or illness. Oral contraception has side effects but these are less in modern times."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491218Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-realise-drugs-tested-healthy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often do not realise that drugs are tested on healthy individuals first."@en ;
  curric:correction """Healthy individuals are used as they will not have symptoms that interfere with the side effects from the drug."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-mistakenly-believe-one-factor
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may mistakenly believe that only one factor can limit the rate of photosynthesis at any given time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson teaches that multiple factors, such as light intensity, carbon dioxide concentration, and temperature, can simultaneously influence the rate of photosynthesis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491236Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-appreciate-safety-laboratory-shared
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils do not always appreciate that safety in the laboratory is a shared responsibility."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure pupils understand the hazards related to both common chemicals and regularly used equipment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491273Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-failing-realise-plateau-rate-graph
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Failing to realise that the plateau on a rate graph can occur because another factor (not named on the axes) has become limiting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores rate graphs in which multiple limiting factors are affecting the rate of photosynthesis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491558Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-larger-surface-area-produces-larger
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a larger surface area produces a larger volume/mass of product."@en ;
  curric:correction """The experiment should help pupils realise they produce the same mass of carbon dioxide when using the same mass of calcium carbonate chips and powder."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491567Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-carbon-allotropes-giant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think all carbon allotropes have giant covalent structures due to strong covalent bonds."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that fullerenes and nanotubes, unlike graphene and diamond, have discrete molecular structures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-understanding-why-carbon-dioxide-produced
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Understanding why carbon dioxide is produced at the anode, when there is no carbon in aluminium oxide."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind students of previous knowledge about combustion reactions. Help them to apply this knowledge to this new situation in the electrolysis cell."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491589Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-recall-order-steps
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils struggle to recall the order of steps required to mathematically process the available information in order to answer the question."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Colour-coding the steps can help pupils remember how many steps are involved. Much practice and perseverance is needed to create and maintain the memory pathway of the mathematical processing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491720Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-prefix-hydro-term
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that the prefix hydro- in the term hydrocarbons means they contain water; also that hydrocarbons and crude oil are synonymous."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use diagrams to show hydrocarbon composition and compare crude oil to pure hydrocarbons, highlighting the difference visually."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491742Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-collision-reactant-particles-results-chemical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That every collision between reactant particles results in a chemical reaction."@en ;
  curric:correction """The slide deck addresses that not every collision between reactant particles results in a chemical reaction. The particles must collide with the activation energy in order for the collision to be successful and a new product be formed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-physical-chemical-changes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse physical and chemical changes and think that all particles look and act like those shown in the particle model."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Give the pupils an array of different examples of physical and chemical reactions and get the pupils to consider if new substances have been produced. Show the pupils, using molymods, how different molecules can be."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-clear-understanding-forces-acting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not have a clear understanding of the forces acting between neutrons and protons in an atomic nucleus."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In simple terms, explain the reasons why some nuclei are unstable in terms of electrostatic repulsion, and include ideas about the strong nuclear force attracting protons and neutrons to each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491908Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-gamma-rays-higher-energy-power
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Gamma rays are always higher energy (or power), or more dangerous, than other frequencies of EM radiation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """EM waves transfer their energy in 'chunks' or 'packets'. The energy transferred by one 'packet' of radiation (and so its ionising ability) does depend on frequency. But the power of a beam of radiation depends on the intensity of the radiation too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.491921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-impossible-predict-outcomes-random-events
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is impossible to predict outcomes for random events such as radioactive decay."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use analogies to show that random nuclear decay can lead to predictable outcomes, such as the randomness in the order popcorn kernels pop, but the predictability of how quickly all the popcorn takes to cook."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-majority-pupils-struggle-differentiate-ionising
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The majority of pupils struggle to differentiate between ionising and non–ionising radiation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explicitly teach that non–ionising radiation is not able to force electrons off atoms – it cannot turn atoms into ions.  What it may be able to do is cause heating by increasing the movement of particles and therefore temperature of the substance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492061Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-magnetic-field-same-electric-field
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A magnetic field is the same as the electric field around a charged object."@en ;
  curric:correction """Demonstrate that an electromagnet does not attract small pieces of tissue paper, as a balloon with a static charge can do."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492075Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-final-velocity-proportional
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that final velocity is proportional to acceleration and do not take into account the time over which an object is accelerating."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Compare how many times greater the calculated accelerations of two sets of readings are compared to how many times greater the final velocities are."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-important-same-person-take-measurements
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It is important for the same person to take all the measurements."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that if the method is a good one then everyone carrying it out carefully should get similar results that show the same pattern (the results are repeatable and reproducible)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492091Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-forget-halogens-diatomic-molecules
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often forget that the halogens are diatomic molecules."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explanation of the bonding to form molecules helps to explain why they exist as diatomic molecules."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492373Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-decrease-temperature-occurring
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can assume that any decrease in temperature occurring when excess reactant is added to an exothermic reaction is because the reaction has become endothermic."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that once the limiting reactant has been used up the exothermic reaction is complete. The addition of excess reactant will only act to cool down the reaction mixture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492380Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-catalysts-increase-amount-product-formed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Catalysts increase the amount of product formed."@en ;
  curric:correction """Catalysts do not affect the quantity of products formed. They increase the rate at which the products are formed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492389Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-link-mole-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils struggle to link a mole to number of particles."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use real world examples of converting volumes / masses into number of particles so pupils become more comfortable converting between moles, number of particles particles and masses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-confuse-subatomic-particle-responsible
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often confuse the subatomic particle responsible for making an atom an isotope, and how isotopes are responsible for the relative atomic masses to 1 d.p."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Practice determining the number of neutrons in multiple isotopes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492409Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-velocity-speed-increasing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that if velocity or speed is increasing, then acceleration must also be increasing. Pupils often don't associate a change in direction at a constant speed with an acceleration."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Before teaching acceleration, consolidate an understanding of the differences between velocity and changes in velocity. Discuss how an object can be accelerating AND travelling at a constant speed (circular motion)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-earths-atmosphere-contained-oxygen-atmospheres
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Earth's atmosphere has always contained oxygen. The atmosphere's composition is static and unchanging."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Clarify the development of oxygen through photosynthesis. Describe how atmospheric composition has evolved over time due to geological and biological processes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-metallic-structure-model-replication-reality
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The metallic structure model is a replication of reality. Therefore, metals contain seawater. The concept of electric current is challenging. Some may think that electrons jump from atom to atom."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss why scientists use models with the pupils, explaining that a model is only as good as what it can explain, so it develops over time. Remind pupils how an electric circuit works before discussing why metals are good conductors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-added-calcium-hydroxide-dissolves-completely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All added calcium hydroxide dissolves completely, and the pH readings are accurate without consistent mixing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Calcium hydroxide has low solubility in water, so not all of it dissolves readily. Consistent mixing ensures uniform pH readings. Without proper mixing, pH readings can be inaccurate, leading to incorrect conclusions about the neutralisation point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.492963Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-struggle-idea-small-atom
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often struggle with the idea of how small an atom actually is. In contrast, how small the nucleus is, relative to the size of the atom."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The use of units and numbers to show the difference in size, e.g. the atom is approximately 10, 000 times larger than the nucleus. The radius of the atom is 0.1nm and the nucleus very small compared to that of the atom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493233Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-abortion-option-following-positive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thinking that abortion is the only option following a positive genetic test result during pregnancy."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores the various options and support that are available to parents who have a high probability of passing on alleles that can affect their child's health."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-chemistry-meaning-strong
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse the chemistry meaning of strong/weak and concentrated/dilute due to the use of these words in everyday conversation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Clear definitions of the words are required with practice opportunities to recognise/describe whether the substances are strong or weak acids and if concentrated or dilute."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-regard-force-property-object
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may regard force as a property of an object, expressing ideas such as ‘the object has a force’ and ‘the object runs out of force’."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Describe forces as interactions between two objects, using the phrasing ‘the force of object A on object B’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-pupils-think-uninsulated-wire
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is very common for pupils to think that uninsulated wire is needed for the coil of an electromagnet."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When discussing an electromagnet, always refer to the insulated wire in its core, which is necessary so the current in each turn adds to the strength of the electromagnet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493621Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-antibiotics-work-pathogens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that antibiotics work on all pathogens."@en ;
  curric:correction """Antibiotics only kill bacteria. Antibiotics can only kill certain bacteria and so the doctor will prescribe the correct one."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-rarely-consider-choice-equipment
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils rarely consider the choice of equipment and its link to the accuracy of the data they collect in a practical."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight that equipment with smaller resolution provides more precise measurements, which can decrease the uncertainty of a calculated mean."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493975Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-energy-lost-created-physical-processes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Energy can be lost or created in physical processes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Always discuss how energy is dissipated to the surroundings when discussing energy transformations, even when dealing with ‘ideal situations’ in which there is no dissipation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.493992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-extension-extra-amount-spring-stretched
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Extension is the extra amount the spring has stretched when a bigger force is applied."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure pupils fully remove each hanging mass between measurements so they see the extension of the spring from its original length each time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.494248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-even-sub-microscopic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often do not understand that even sub–microscopic particles have a mass and volume which affect the density of a substance."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the anomaly of ice floating on water to consolidate understanding that molecules have mass and that the spacing of water molecules can affect density."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.494256Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-menstrual-cycle-linked-reproduction-hormones
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the menstrual cycle is not linked with reproduction; that hormones only control mood."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Diagrams to show the clear effect of hormones on changes in the menstrual cycle and discuss the importance of the process to fertilisation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.494845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-spelling-noble-re-nobel-concept
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Spelling of noble re- Nobel and the concept of why they were given this name, i.e. due to having a full outer shell of electrons which means they do not need to bond with other elements."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the name noble was due to the fact that they are so unreactive and did not need to bond with other elements due to already having a full outer shell of electrons making them so stable."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.495021Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-water-samples-boil-100-c
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All water samples boil at 100°C."@en ;
  curric:correction """If a water sample is impure, the boiling point of water increases. The greater the amount of impurities in a water sample, the larger the temperature range over which it boils."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.495209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-cells-approximately-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think that all cells are approximately the same size."@en ;
  curric:correction """Calculations in the deck will allow pupils to compare the relative sizes of cells. It might be helpful to draw extra attention to this point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.495236Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-key-terminology-many
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse key terminology, as many words are similar, and confuse electrolysis with physical methods of separation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the keywords and provide plenty of opportunity for them to be used in the correct context. Compare electrolysis to physical methods of separation, such as filtration, and explain that chemical reactions occur at the electrodes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.495252Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ionic-equations-include-ions-involved
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Ionic equations only include ions involved in the reaction, not all ions in the reaction mixture."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Stress the difference between reacting ions and spectator ions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.495649Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-individuals-helpless-combatting-climate-change
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """As individuals we are helpless in combatting climate change. Technology alone can solve climate issues."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the impact of collective individual actions, especially in supporting national and international actions (including legislation) that cause appropriate change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.495665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-ideas-temperature-energy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils confuse ideas about temperature and energy."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use examples in different contexts to develop and consolidate ideas about differences between temperature and energy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.495695Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-salts-either-completely-soluble-completely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All salts are either completely soluble or completely insoluble in water."@en ;
  curric:correction """Not all salts follow a strict 'soluble' or 'insoluble' rule. Some salts have limited solubility, meaning they dissolve only to a certain extent. Solubility rules help us predict the solubility of common salts, but there are always exceptions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496188Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-renewable-energy-resources-expensive-fossil
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Renewable energy resources are more expensive than fossil fuels and cannot meet the demand for electricity on their own."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Compare the cost of renewable energy resources with that of fossil fuels and explore advantages in energy storage technologies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496220Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-reversible-reaction-go
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that a reversible reaction will always go to completion in one direction before reversing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that in a reversible reaction, if the conditions allow it, both the forward and backward reaction can occur at the same time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-calculating-energy-kinetic-store-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When calculating energy in the kinetic store, pupils often work out ½ mv and then square everything, rather than just the speed."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scaffold calculations to show how kinetic energy is calculated, taking pupils through how to do this on their calculators without making a mistake."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496517Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-equation-speed-wave-v-f
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """In the equation for the speed of a wave, v = f x λ, speed is dependent on frequency and/or wavelength."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that the speed of a wave depends only on the wave medium and not on frequency or wavelength."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-mistake-excess-base-salt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can sometimes mistake the excess base for the salt formed as it is a solid."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise at the beginning of the experiment what soluble means and that the salt will be initially obtained dissolved in water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-fail-understand-excess-reactant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes fail to understand that excess reactant particles remain in the reaction mixture after the reaction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide a balanced equation and challenge pupils to draw diagrams of a final mixture, stressing that excess particles would also be present.  Challenge pupils to consider how the product could be extracted from the excess particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496911Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-forget-gases-produced-metals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often forget that gases are produced when metals and metal carbonates react with acids."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the tests for the gases as a way to remember that they are produced. Writing balanced symbol equations also helps as the pupils can see what elements would be present in the products formed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496942Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-decide-scales-needed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils can struggle to decide on the scales needed for an axis on a graph."@en ;
  curric:correction """Suggest a suitable scale that will fit on the graph paper they will use or use a computer to draw graphs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-white-surfaces-poor-absorbers-visible
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """White surfaces are always poor absorbers of visible light so they must also always be poor absorbers and emitters of infrared."""@en ;
  curric:correction """White paint is a good absorber and emitter of IR. Colour is not always a good guide to effectiveness at emitting/absorbing IR, except for dark+dull surfaces usually being good emitters/absorbers and shiny metal surfaces being poor emitters/absorbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.496994Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-trend-reactivity-group
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils can confuse the trend in reactivity down the group."@en ;
  curric:correction """The practical reacting the metals with water helps to memorably demonstrate the trend, however it is important to ensure that pupils can explain why this happens."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497010Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-hard-remember-formed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils find it hard to remember what is formed at each electrode."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils about the electrolysis rules and provide opportunities for them to apply the rules to different electrolytes. Use animations to show the ions present in brine and how they move in the electrolysis cell."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-halogen-solutions-coloured-difficult-determine
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Halogen solutions are coloured and sometimes it can be difficult to determine colour changes during displacement reactions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Displacement of iodine gives the darkest colour change (turns brown), while bromine will provide one which is lighter (turns orange)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-combustion-complete-producing-co-water
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All combustion is complete, producing only CO₂ and water."@en ;
  curric:correction "Highlight the differences between complete and incomplete combustion."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497169Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-several-misconceptions-associated-properties-such
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There are several misconceptions associated with properties such as when something dissolves it disappears, electrical conductivity is a flow of electrons rather than charge."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When discussing electrical conductivity, emphasise the idea of electrical conductivity being a flow charge with ions behaving as charge carriers. The electron transfer that occurs during ion formation is nothing to do with conductivity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497184Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believing-sustainability-someone-elses
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students believing that sustainability is someone else's responsibility."@en ;
  curric:correction """Everyone needs to reduce, reuse and recycle to ensure sustainable development. The slide deck gives examples of products that can be recycled and the benefits of reducing, reusing and recycling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497221Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-because-solute-longer-seen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some think that because a solute can no longer be seen, or that a solvent becomes coloured when a solute dissolves, that the creation of a solution is a chemical change."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Create a salt solution, then evaporate the water (leaving salt crystals) to demonstrate that the salt and water have not chemically combined and therefore dissolving (to create a solution) is a physical change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497269Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-increase-atmospheric-carbon-dioxide
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thinking that an increase in atmospheric carbon dioxide will be beneficial by increasing photosynthesis and producing more food."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson explores why the negative effects of increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide outweigh any benefits from increased rate of photosynthesis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.497998Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-atmosphere-mostly-oxygen-same-atmospheric
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The atmosphere is mostly oxygen. The same atmospheric conditions exist at all heights."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the atmosphere is ~80% nitrogen and ~20% oxygen. Discuss how atmospheric conditions vary with altitude, affecting oxygen availability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.498367Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-simply-ensuring-fair
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils think that simply ensuring a fair test will improve data collecting in a practical."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Evaluating a practical is an often overlooked skill.  Challenge pupils to focus on the equipment chosen and/or the method followed to consider how better data might be collected."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.498830Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-understand-heating-constant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes struggle to understand that 'heating to constant mass' takes time and multiple measurements."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Link the idea that atoms rearrange during a reaction and that for all atoms of a substance to be oxidised, enough oxygen must be present. If the product measurements show a 'constant mass' we can be confident that complete oxidation has occurred."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.498846Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-mass-crucible-contents
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the mass of the crucible and contents will not change during the reaction because the lid is closed, believing that all gases produced remain inside."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that even with the crucible lid on, gases like carbon dioxide & water vapour formed during decomposition can escape around the edges. This leads to a decrease in mass, which is crucial for calculating the stoichiometry based on the mass loss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.498918Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-process-osmosis-direction-movement-high
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The process of osmosis, the direction of movement from high to low water concentration, and the effect that this has on plant cells in terms of turgidity and flaccidity are frequently confused."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Errors are explored, explained and questioned, and clear demonstrations of turgidity and flaccidity and the effects that these have on a plant are demonstrated. This will be reinforced by observation of these processes using a light microscope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.499119Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-overshoot-end-point-especially
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often overshoot the end point, especially on their first attempt at a titration."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Pupils will need to work on their dexterity, often with a partner, to ensure the flow of titrant is slow enough from the burette, and that their swirling technique allows ample mixing of the solutions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.499381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-terms-force-momentum
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often confuse the terms force and momentum."@en ;
  curric:correction """Make explicit the understanding that forces change the motion of an object, and that the motion of an object  (that a force can change) can be described by its momentum."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.499543Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-use-physics-equations-without
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often use physics equations without understanding, leading to errors."@en ;
  curric:correction """Develop a qualitative understanding of potential difference, current and resistance before combining them mathematically. Use the equation as a shorthand for an already understood relationship between them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.500161Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-measurements-repeatable-precise-accurate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "If measurements are repeatable (or precise) then they will also be accurate."@en ;
  curric:correction """Repeatable (or precise) measurements may involve a systematic error making them inaccurate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.500168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-teaching-pupils-understand-specific-heat
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Often, after teaching, pupils often do not understand what specific heat capacity means."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss the size of a substance’s specific heat capacity in terms of how hard it is to heat up a certain mass of the substance and of how much energy needs to be transferred to heat it up."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.500189Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-systematic-error-spotted-taking-repeat
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A systematic error can be spotted by taking repeat readings."@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss why the heating of the beaker when measuring specific heat capacity of water will always increase energy measured by the same proportion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.500774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-metal-acid-react-together
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Thinking that a metal and acid react together to produce salt and water."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use symbol equations to show how hydrogen is produced, rather than water, due to the absence of oxygen atoms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.500862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-struggle-distinguish-phytoextraction-bioleaching
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students struggle to distinguish between phytoextraction and bioleaching."@en ;
  curric:correction "Reinforce that the term 'phyto' is a combining form meaning 'plant'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501155Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-easily-confuse-empirical-molecular
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils easily confuse empirical and molecular formula."@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide multiple examples of formula and challenge pupils to distinguish them as molecular or empirical formula; if the former, push pupils to suggest the molecule's empirical formula."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mains-appliances-draw-their-electricity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mains appliances draw all their electricity from the live wire, without need for a complete circuit."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show pupils live and neutral wires connected to a AC connections on a power pack (you can use individual wires taken from mains cables) to show complete circuits are necessary, and that mains cables contain these wires."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-getting-electrons-confused-many-side
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Getting the electrons confused; how many and which side of the half equations to write them on."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When writing a half equation, electrons should be added and not taken away and so should go on the side of the equation where they are added. All charges must cancel each other out and the atoms on each side of the equation balance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501257Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-show-spectator-ions-ionic-equation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To show the spectator ions in an ionic equation."@en ;
  curric:correction """Spectator ions are ions that remain the same throughout a reaction. They are not included in the ionic equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501264Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-incorrectly-interpret-subscript-stoichiometric
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some pupils incorrectly interpret subscript and stoichiometric values in a balanced symbol equation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Both subscript and stoichiometric values represent ratios.  Subscripts indicate ratios *within* substances; stoichiometry. Molar ratios *between* substances in a reaction.  Much practice distinguishing between/ interpreting these is time well spent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-mean-rate-reaction
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse the mean rate of reaction with the instantaneous rate of reaction, thinking they are the same or not understanding the distinction between the two."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The tasks give pupils s the opportunity to distinguish between mean and instantaneous rate of reaction by calculating both from the same set of data."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501301Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-covalent-bond-shared-pair-electrons
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The covalent bond is the shared pair of electrons; both electrons must come from different atoms. The central atom  is responsible for the formation of covalent bonds as they want a full outer shell."""@en ;
  curric:correction """All chemical bonds are an electrostatic force of attraction between positive and negative charges. The sharing of electrons is the process by which covalent bonds are formed. Avoid using anthropomorphic analogies to explain how covalent bonds form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-struggle-explain-transpiration-affected
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some students may struggle to explain how transpiration is affected by a number of factors, even though these factors have the same effects on everyday activities such as drying hair or clothes."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Links between these everyday events and transpiration have been made and illustrated simultaneously, so students make the link between the two."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-greenhouse-gases-artificial-harmful-increasing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All greenhouse gases are artificial and harmful. Increasing any greenhouse gas is bad."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise and explain the natural occurrence and necessity of greenhouse gases. Discuss the effect of human activity increasing amounts of greenhouse gases at a very fast rate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.501655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-understanding-models-used-represent-chemical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Understanding that the models used to represent chemical story do not tell the complete story. Different models can be used to explain different aspects of bonding, but they all have limitations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Avoid telling your class that the model is wrong; rather stress its limitations. Stress the idea that as we learn more about bonding, we will be able to use more sophisticated models to show and explain more key ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.502275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plants-absorb-carbon-dioxide-human
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Plants can absorb all of the carbon dioxide that human activity adds to the atmosphere."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Talk to the pupils about what happens to the carbon dioxide absorbed by plants so that they understand how the size and number of plants determine the maximum amount of carbon dioxide they can store."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.505380Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-voltage-drop-across-power-lines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The voltage (drop) across power lines is the same as the voltage they transmit."@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend time to clarify that the power transmitted depends on the p.d. between the live and neutral wires, and power dissipated depends on the drop in voltage from one end of a live wire to the other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.506668Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ions-formed-because-atoms-want
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Ions are not formed because atoms 'want' or 'need' a full outer electron shell. Pupils often find standard notation difficult and get confused about when to use superscript and subscript."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is important that pupils understand that atoms do not have 'wants' or 'needs'. Emphasise that the driving force for the formation of atoms is an increase in stability when the outer electron shell is full."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.506686Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-able-complete-calculations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may assume that being able to complete calculations by substituting numbers into an equation is the same as fully understanding the relationship."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Include questions for which pupils are required to explain their understanding."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.506717Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-apply-equations-incorrectly-spot
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often apply equations incorrectly or do not spot obvious errors when using them due to not thinking about the science."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask pupils to describe what happens for each example in relation to their answers to problems set."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.506723Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-oxidation-reduction-involving
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can confuse oxidation and reduction when involving electrons. They often mistake a positive charge on an ion as meaning electrons have been added and vice versa for negative ions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is very important to teach from first principles what causes the charges and then work up to half equations where the pupils can see the electrons in the equations, finally combining these to form ionic equations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.506997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-alpha-beta-particles-gamma-radiation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Alpha and beta particles and gamma radiation are radioactive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Differentiate between radioactive particles that can emit radiation and the radiation itself. Radiation consists of fast moving particles or radiation that can cause ionisation because their electric fields interact with those of outer electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.507166Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-travelling-exceptionally-high-speed-speed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Travelling at exceptionally high speed through a speed camera means that it will not be able to measure your speed accurately and so it will not trigger."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Tell pupils that speed cameras use radio waves which travel at 300 000 000 m/s. They can accurately measure the speed of objects travelling at thousands of metres per second."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-19T08:26:10.509104Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
